WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.780 --> 00:00:05.670
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN:
Well, good evening.

00:00:05.670 --> 00:00:07.220
Hello.

00:00:07.220 --> 00:00:08.950
My name is Jonathan
Zittrain, and I

00:00:08.950 --> 00:00:12.620
am so pleased to be
here with you all today

00:00:12.620 --> 00:00:16.379
to hear from John Palfrey on
the occasion of the release

00:00:16.379 --> 00:00:21.150
of his book, BiblioTech-- Why
Libraries Matter More Than

00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:22.930
Ever in The Age of Google.

00:00:22.930 --> 00:00:25.470
Nicely focused group to get
Google in there, as well.

00:00:25.470 --> 00:00:27.240
It's very nice, a
googleable term.

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:27.580
JOHN PALFREY: It's all SEO.

00:00:27.580 --> 00:00:28.538
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Yes.

00:00:31.232 --> 00:00:34.360
First just logistics--
this is being recorded.

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:37.760
So your image, if not soul, are
being captured for posterity.

00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:41.600
It is not being live
webcast, but it will probably

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:44.060
go up later unless something
truly substantively

00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:45.610
catastrophic happens.

00:00:45.610 --> 00:00:47.790
And what else should we know?

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:51.309
We're going to go into around
7:00, 7:15, at which point

00:00:51.309 --> 00:00:53.350
there will be a reception
next door that can also

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:56.055
spill over onto
the outdoor patio,

00:00:56.055 --> 00:00:59.290
to which everybody is invited.

00:00:59.290 --> 00:01:04.560
And John has done about
a dozen talks so far

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:08.190
on the road for this
book, so our challenge

00:01:08.190 --> 00:01:10.940
is to ask him questions
that he has yet

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:14.160
to hear from the road,
which is very exciting.

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:17.120
He's spoken to a group as
small as about 30 or 40

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:20.240
at the Andover Bookstore,
and as big as 1,000

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:24.194
at a conference called
Computers and Libraries?

00:01:24.194 --> 00:01:25.360
JOHN PALFREY: Yes, that was.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:27.026
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN:
Good eponymous title,

00:01:27.026 --> 00:01:32.150
a solid non-focused group--
Computers and Libraries.

00:01:32.150 --> 00:01:35.090
They ought to alternate every
year, Libraries and Computers.

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:35.620
Anyway.

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:37.495
JOHN PALFREY: I'll send
them that suggestion.

00:01:37.495 --> 00:01:39.070
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN:
Yes, very good.

00:01:39.070 --> 00:01:40.400
So how to introduce John?

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:47.920
John is a lawyer-- that gets
a chortle through the room.

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:51.160
But that's OK, he's an
unpracticing lawyer,

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:53.730
unless you think of practicing
in the larger sense.

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:55.460
Now, he did do a turn
at Ropes and Gray

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:57.524
before being rescued
by the Berkman Center.

00:01:57.524 --> 00:01:59.190
JOHN PALFREY: I was
there almost as long

00:01:59.190 --> 00:02:01.384
as Yochai Benkler,
who is also here.

00:02:01.384 --> 00:02:02.300
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Ah.

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:05.840
I forget that Yochai also
did a turn at Ropes and Gray.

00:02:05.840 --> 00:02:07.980
Good times.

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:13.930
But John worked for the EPA
for a while, regional office.

00:02:13.930 --> 00:02:17.221
You were kind of in a
political sort of role, yes?

00:02:17.221 --> 00:02:19.220
Anything more you want
to tell us about the EPA?

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:20.011
JOHN PALFREY: Nope.

00:02:20.011 --> 00:02:20.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:20.610 --> 00:02:23.090
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: As you can
see, it was a political role.

00:02:23.090 --> 00:02:28.230
And John was Executive
Director of the Berkman Center

00:02:28.230 --> 00:02:32.000
and was the one who really
put the center into workdrive

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.660
and took it from a kind of
small place in a hallway

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:39.350
to a larger place that met fire
codes much better than it did

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:45.860
before, and that really had
an inclusiveness to his way

00:02:45.860 --> 00:02:48.790
of running the place that has
been reflected in the substance

00:02:48.790 --> 00:02:52.680
that he has thought about
since, a book on interop

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:53.706
and interoperability.

00:02:53.706 --> 00:02:56.690
And this in a way is a
book about interoperability

00:02:56.690 --> 00:02:59.800
and thinking about
the mortar that

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:02.750
cements the various
bricks we have together

00:03:02.750 --> 00:03:05.610
in ways that keep civil society.

00:03:05.610 --> 00:03:07.980
That's so much, I think,
of what John thinks about.

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:10.240
And of course, day to
day now, after having

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:12.590
done a turn as a
professor here, director

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:15.870
of the library here at
the law school, and now

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:20.500
is the head of school at
Phillips Andover, which

00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:24.880
he is in the process completely
reinventing and doing

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:27.930
all sorts of cool things
which we might hear about.

00:03:27.930 --> 00:03:29.790
So John is just
one of these people

00:03:29.790 --> 00:03:36.400
who is not a podium thumper,
doesn't shout to be heard.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:41.050
He simply has really persuasive
and interesting and thoughtful

00:03:41.050 --> 00:03:44.890
things to say, and
the kindest ethos,

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:47.040
both at the institutional
and personal level,

00:03:47.040 --> 00:03:51.510
somebody that I find
myself going to for counsel

00:03:51.510 --> 00:03:53.830
and many, many others as well.

00:03:53.830 --> 00:03:55.250
And I have yet to
receive a bill.

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:58.510
So that's how I know he's
really not a practicing lawyer.

00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:00.760
So John, we're so
pleased to see you.

00:04:00.760 --> 00:04:03.960
Note that in some
quirk of things,

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:08.581
there are exactly three copies
of this book available for sale

00:04:08.581 --> 00:04:09.330
around the corner.

00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:10.270
JOHN PALFREY: That's either a
good sign or a really bad sign.

00:04:10.270 --> 00:04:11.228
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Yes.

00:04:11.228 --> 00:04:13.670
But they will also, because
they only have three copies,

00:04:13.670 --> 00:04:18.410
put you on the list to order one
on layaway at a 30% discount.

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:21.480
So that's a good
deal of the evening.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:23.310
John, you are 100% here.

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:25.520
Thank you so much for
spending time with us tonight.

00:04:25.520 --> 00:04:27.127
We're so excited
what you have to say.

00:04:27.127 --> 00:04:28.460
JOHN PALFREY: Thank you so much.

00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:32.220
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:35.090
And thank you all for coming.

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:37.330
This is very touching to
see such a great crowd.

00:04:37.330 --> 00:04:39.010
I feel like I'm
coming home in a way,

00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:41.132
and to see so many
people that I've

00:04:41.132 --> 00:04:43.590
worked with, both at the Berkman
Center and the Harvard Law

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:45.750
School Library and the
Harvard libraries broadly.

00:04:45.750 --> 00:04:48.380
I'm truly, truly
grateful to see you here.

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:51.330
This book that I have
written is a love letter

00:04:51.330 --> 00:04:54.410
to libraries and to
those who work in them,

00:04:54.410 --> 00:04:56.125
the librarians in particular.

00:04:56.125 --> 00:04:58.030
It is also, I hope,
an argument for why

00:04:58.030 --> 00:05:00.650
libraries are so
crucial, especially

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:01.850
in the age of Google.

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:04.440
And all of that I learned from
those people in this room,

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:07.542
and I'm really grateful for
all of your help in doing it.

00:05:07.542 --> 00:05:10.000
I'm going to try to talk for
no more than 20 or 25 minutes,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.708
and then hopefully
get into conversation.

00:05:11.708 --> 00:05:14.200
I would love to hear much
of what is on your minds

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:15.700
and be challenged,
as Jonathan said,

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:19.090
with questions I haven't
yet heard on this book tour.

00:05:19.090 --> 00:05:21.550
This may the only
place on my book tour

00:05:21.550 --> 00:05:23.530
where somebody will know
what this actually is.

00:05:23.530 --> 00:05:26.374
Is there anybody who
recognizes this picture?

00:05:26.374 --> 00:05:27.290
AUDIENCE: Your office?

00:05:27.290 --> 00:05:27.998
JOHN PALFREY: No.

00:05:27.998 --> 00:05:30.128
It comes from--
yes, [INAUDIBLE]?

00:05:30.128 --> 00:05:31.880
AUDIENCE: Oliver
Wendell Holmes' library?

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:33.338
JOHN PALFREY: Yes,
that's so great.

00:05:33.338 --> 00:05:34.880
This is the first
time someone has

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:36.390
known the answer
to that question,

00:05:36.390 --> 00:05:37.910
and I ask it everywhere.

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:41.780
This is the personal library of
Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr., who

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:43.960
of course was a professor here.

00:05:43.960 --> 00:05:46.880
But this was actually his
home in Washington, DC.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:49.600
And I love this picture for
a whole bunch of reasons.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:52.250
It reminds me of the Harvard Law
School Library and the awesome

00:05:52.250 --> 00:05:54.290
librarians and archivists
who work in it,

00:05:54.290 --> 00:05:56.930
and the fact that they digitized
this amazing collection

00:05:56.930 --> 00:05:58.200
of Oliver Wendell Holmes'.

00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:01.620
But it also to me is a
great challenge to all of us

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.620
when we think about
libraries and the libraries

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:04.203
of the future.

00:06:04.203 --> 00:06:07.410
And the reason I see it as a
challenge is this room to me

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:10.080
is really, really
appealing-- the idea

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:12.520
that you could have
a space in your home

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:15.630
that is surrounded by books in
this way and sit in that chair

00:06:15.630 --> 00:06:17.450
and think of all
the great opinions

00:06:17.450 --> 00:06:18.464
that Holmes thought up.

00:06:18.464 --> 00:06:19.880
Now, we know he
had a few clangers

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:21.280
and so forth, so he
thought up some bad ones.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:22.970
And maybe he didn't do it here.

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:26.710
But just the idea that he was
inspired by sitting there.

00:06:26.710 --> 00:06:28.910
And for many of us, we
work with young people.

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:32.690
I now live with and work
with about 1,100 teenagers,

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:35.090
and I think a ton about
what inspires them.

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:36.940
What kind of space
would inspire them?

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:39.000
What kind of a
library space would?

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.050
And for most of our
teenagers, my guess

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:43.870
is that this might be a
cool and inspiring space,

00:06:43.870 --> 00:06:46.090
but for almost none of
them would they sit up,

00:06:46.090 --> 00:06:48.830
swirl around that chair,
and then pull one of those

00:06:48.830 --> 00:06:49.794
off the shelf.

00:06:49.794 --> 00:06:52.460
For those of us who've worked in
the Harvard Law School Library,

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:54.990
I was always struck by the
fact that we were almost always

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:56.190
full as a library.

00:06:56.190 --> 00:06:58.340
Cheek by jowl those
kids were there.

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:00.190
Very often they
had those approved

00:07:00.190 --> 00:07:01.709
Harvard Law School Library mugs.

00:07:01.709 --> 00:07:03.000
And they had a casebook, right?

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.070
And they were highlighting
away on the casebook,

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:07.590
but they weren't doing a
ton of pulling statutes

00:07:07.590 --> 00:07:09.650
or other things off
the shelves-- almost

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:12.170
never, at least in the big
reading room, literally never.

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:14.000
And maybe if they had a
great reference librarian

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.040
they might have found something.

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:17.170
But by and large, they were
there for other reasons.

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:17.670
Right?

00:07:17.670 --> 00:07:19.801
They are there probably
right now studying away

00:07:19.801 --> 00:07:20.550
for other reasons.

00:07:20.550 --> 00:07:23.236
And I think our challenge,
in a way, in a digital era

00:07:23.236 --> 00:07:24.610
is to come up with
something that

00:07:24.610 --> 00:07:27.890
is as powerful and
appealing a space for kids

00:07:27.890 --> 00:07:31.221
as a learning space and as
an environment in libraries.

00:07:31.221 --> 00:07:33.470
And I think that's the
challenge back on all of us who

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:35.655
are trying to design and
to create these spaces

00:07:35.655 --> 00:07:37.000
in an exciting way.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:40.120
And I think we do this against
a backdrop where libraries

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:42.110
are to some extent in peril.

00:07:42.110 --> 00:07:44.430
Now, I stand in a room,
I realize, at Harvard,

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:47.780
the place where unbelievable
support for libraries exists.

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:49.887
But even within Harvard,
we know that there

00:07:49.887 --> 00:07:51.720
are different schools
that support libraries

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:52.920
at different levels.

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:53.700
Our dean is here.

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:54.450
Meet Dean Minow.

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:55.600
Thank you for being here.

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:58.901
Thank you for being a lover of
libraries, not just evidenced

00:07:58.901 --> 00:08:01.150
by the fact that you're here
but because of all you do

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:03.020
to make libraries great here.

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:04.830
But even within the
context of Harvard,

00:08:04.830 --> 00:08:06.710
we went through
several year period

00:08:06.710 --> 00:08:07.940
of quite a bit of transition.

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:09.430
And I was a part of that too.

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:11.880
And we know that there are
times when libraries are

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:13.380
under a great deal of pressure.

00:08:13.380 --> 00:08:14.840
That is true in
academic settings,

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:19.325
and obviously this is a
difficult context for many.

00:08:19.325 --> 00:08:21.700
But it's particularly true,
I think, in public libraries.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:23.875
And as I've traveled around
in school libraries--

00:08:23.875 --> 00:08:26.610
the 100,000 or so school
libraries around the country--

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:28.300
very often people
have a funny view

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:30.540
that libraries aren't maybe
as useful as they once

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:32.090
were, which I think
is exactly wrong,

00:08:32.090 --> 00:08:33.600
which is why I wrote this book.

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:35.607
This is a quote from
an Amazon review

00:08:35.607 --> 00:08:36.690
by somebody I do not know.

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:37.815
His name is David Weinberg.

00:08:37.815 --> 00:08:39.919
It is not David
Weinberger our friend.

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:42.710
But this was a not
particularly flattering review

00:08:42.710 --> 00:08:46.372
on Amazon of my book, and
it was disagreeing basically

00:08:46.372 --> 00:08:48.080
with the premise of
the importance of it.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:50.570
But I thought it was a
particularly good view that

00:08:50.570 --> 00:08:53.410
sums up what some
people think, and it

00:08:53.410 --> 00:08:55.240
is a prevailing view out there.

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:58.110
I realized often also when
I was reading the book

00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:00.950
that one of the most common
conversations that I had

00:09:00.950 --> 00:09:03.930
after becoming the Director of
the Harvard Law School Library

00:09:03.930 --> 00:09:06.080
was one at a backyard
barbecue or a cocktail

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:08.050
party, and someone would
come up to me and say,

00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:08.966
so what are you up to?

00:09:08.966 --> 00:09:10.750
And I would say,
I'm just becoming

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:12.000
the director of this library.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.830
And then two seconds later
the person would interrupt me

00:09:14.830 --> 00:09:16.520
and say, oh, wait
a minute, libraries

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:17.210
aren't as useful anymore.

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:18.186
You're the digital guy.

00:09:18.186 --> 00:09:19.310
You're getting rid of them.

00:09:19.310 --> 00:09:20.400
You're getting rid
of all the books.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:21.640
And then they'd
have walked away.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:23.780
In this sense, I never had the
chance to kind of grab them

00:09:23.780 --> 00:09:26.160
and say, no, no, no, libraries
are more important than ever

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:27.160
and here's what we have to do.

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:28.530
And so that's why I
wrote the book in a way,

00:09:28.530 --> 00:09:30.696
was to answer that question
for all those people who

00:09:30.696 --> 00:09:34.037
walked away from me at parties.

00:09:34.037 --> 00:09:36.120
They're not probably going
to be reading the book.

00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:37.430
I get the irony of that.

00:09:37.430 --> 00:09:41.005
But I still felt I had
to win the argument.

00:09:41.005 --> 00:09:43.020
But I say it in a
serious tone, which

00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:45.940
is we recognize that in
many communities, when

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:48.540
there is a choice between
money for police and fire

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:50.360
and education and other
important things--

00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:52.390
and this is true in my
hometown now of Andover,

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:54.410
too-- the library doesn't
get as much support.

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:57.290
The support is eroding for
libraries in these communities,

00:09:57.290 --> 00:10:00.570
and I think we need to
reverse that polarity.

00:10:00.570 --> 00:10:03.710
We do this also, though, I
think, in the context, at least

00:10:03.710 --> 00:10:06.440
in the United States,
of an amazing culture

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:08.710
of support for libraries
and a history of support

00:10:08.710 --> 00:10:09.750
for libraries.

00:10:09.750 --> 00:10:12.370
This image comes from our
hometown of Boston right

00:10:12.370 --> 00:10:13.620
across the river.

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:15.510
Every time I see
this I get chills

00:10:15.510 --> 00:10:17.960
down my spine, the
idea of free to all;

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:21.620
the idea that the big municipal
public libraries started right

00:10:21.620 --> 00:10:24.870
here about 150 years ago,
and with an incredibly

00:10:24.870 --> 00:10:28.810
simple democratic premise--
the basic idea that information

00:10:28.810 --> 00:10:31.950
should be free, knowledge should
be free, to anyone, regardless

00:10:31.950 --> 00:10:33.230
of their ability to pay.

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:36.860
And this was something that
is in the cradle of the Athens

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:39.530
that we created here in
Boston, the middle of our city

00:10:39.530 --> 00:10:40.400
in Copley Square.

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:42.670
And so we have a
history of making

00:10:42.670 --> 00:10:45.160
this kind of amazing
support for our communities,

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:46.430
for our democracies.

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:48.760
And part of what I worry
about in this moment of peril

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:51.430
for libraries is that we
will lose sight of that,

00:10:51.430 --> 00:10:53.910
and that oddly, we
actually might backtrack.

00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:56.920
We might actually have less
access in our democracy

00:10:56.920 --> 00:10:59.516
to information in the digital
age than in an analog age.

00:10:59.516 --> 00:11:00.640
And that would be terrible.

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:03.060
That would be, I
think, perverse.

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:05.620
I think that's true for
a variety of reasons.

00:11:05.620 --> 00:11:07.710
And a simplistic
version of that argument

00:11:07.710 --> 00:11:10.850
is to say, increasingly, as
knowledge moves to the cloud,

00:11:10.850 --> 00:11:13.680
one could imagine it being
vastly more available,

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:15.600
that anybody with
one of these devices

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.740
could get access to
whatever they wanted.

00:11:17.740 --> 00:11:19.448
But there are a couple
reasons why that's

00:11:19.448 --> 00:11:21.250
not so simple or so true.

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:25.050
One is if you look at the
owners of the cloud in essence,

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:26.470
they're almost
all private firms.

00:11:26.470 --> 00:11:29.840
They're almost all parties that
are private companies and doing

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:31.790
it for profit-- which
is not a bad thing,

00:11:31.790 --> 00:11:34.630
and this is not an
anti-corporate screed so much

00:11:34.630 --> 00:11:37.746
as to say public
spaces in cyberspace

00:11:37.746 --> 00:11:39.370
have been things that
we've had to win.

00:11:39.370 --> 00:11:41.953
It's what Jonathan Zittrain and
Yochai Benkler and the Berkman

00:11:41.953 --> 00:11:46.080
Center have had to create and
really care for and establish.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:48.430
As we hurtle to a
cloud-based environment,

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:51.360
by and large we turn to private
players like Amazon and others

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:52.300
to store our stuff.

00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:56.050
So in a very simple
mode, if we increasingly

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:58.740
create our materials and
put them in private hands

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:01.650
as opposed to, say, in the
public hands-- or roughly

00:12:01.650 --> 00:12:04.130
speaking, public-spirited
hands of libraries

00:12:04.130 --> 00:12:08.320
and the research universities
that have libraries--

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:10.815
I think that is a
dangerous thing.

00:12:10.815 --> 00:12:12.900
There are many other ways
in which it's tricky,

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:14.108
and we can come back to that.

00:12:14.108 --> 00:12:15.880
But I think it is
something worth worrying

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:17.290
about a little bit.

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:19.760
There's a way to make
this a bit more precise,

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:22.140
which is for those who've
worked in libraries,

00:12:22.140 --> 00:12:25.320
you know that it's not
always possible for libraries

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:27.780
to do exactly in the
digital age what they've

00:12:27.780 --> 00:12:29.250
done in the physical age.

00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:32.340
One of the ways in which this is
true is the lending of ebooks.

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:34.450
So by and large,
publishers have made

00:12:34.450 --> 00:12:37.060
it tricky to lend
ebooks on the same terms

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:39.110
that you could lend
a physical book.

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:40.660
This is where it
is relevant that we

00:12:40.660 --> 00:12:43.770
are at a school, of course,
because in fact they're treated

00:12:43.770 --> 00:12:45.190
in two really different ways.

00:12:45.190 --> 00:12:47.857
The background law for
lending stuff like this

00:12:47.857 --> 00:12:49.190
is actually really, really good.

00:12:49.190 --> 00:12:52.230
The background copyright, in
a simple sense, is positive.

00:12:52.230 --> 00:12:54.190
Which is, libraries
for hundreds of years

00:12:54.190 --> 00:12:56.000
have been able to buy
something like this

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:57.496
and then do more
or less whatever

00:12:57.496 --> 00:12:58.620
they wanted with it, right?

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:00.453
You could bring it to
a secondhand book shop

00:13:00.453 --> 00:13:02.510
and sell it, or you could
lend it as many times

00:13:02.510 --> 00:13:04.051
as you wanted or
you could tear it up

00:13:04.051 --> 00:13:06.480
or you could digitize it
and do lots of things.

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:08.700
But it turns out that if
you get that same book

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:10.740
and you put it on
one of these devices

00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:14.890
and a library is wishing to get
it on terms that it can license

00:13:14.890 --> 00:13:17.050
to someone else, all of a
sudden it is governed not

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:19.424
by the background copyright
law so much as it is governed

00:13:19.424 --> 00:13:22.020
by the contract law that
the company sets up,

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:23.880
the publisher sets
up with the library.

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:25.754
And for all those who've
worked in libraries,

00:13:25.754 --> 00:13:28.870
you know that you can't always
get e-books on as good terms

00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:30.220
as you can get physical books.

00:13:30.220 --> 00:13:32.920
And some of the outcomes
are perverse and bizarre,

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:34.720
like you can't read it aloud.

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:36.970
Those are some of the
worst of the terms.

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:40.000
Some of the other terms
have been the 26-lend rule.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:41.730
Does anybody remember
that great offering

00:13:41.730 --> 00:13:43.330
from a publisher,
the notion that you

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:47.090
could get one of these for
whatever the full price was

00:13:47.090 --> 00:13:49.482
and Jonathan and I could lend
it back and forth 26 times,

00:13:49.482 --> 00:13:50.940
and then of course
it would go away

00:13:50.940 --> 00:13:52.600
because it would have worn out.

00:13:52.600 --> 00:13:53.590
Right?

00:13:53.590 --> 00:13:56.340
That premise didn't
work out all that well.

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:58.140
The basic idea, though,
is that it has not

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:01.550
been possible for libraries
to get digital materials on as

00:14:01.550 --> 00:14:04.130
good a deal, or
in fact, as often,

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:06.670
as they could get
it in physical form.

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:09.820
And this, I think, is
a dangerous premise.

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:11.720
It's also the case
that when it is

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:16.370
a contract between the
company and the library,

00:14:16.370 --> 00:14:18.780
there's also something
tricky behind it with respect

00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:21.200
to the ability to store it
over a long period of time too.

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:23.300
So if the point
is we're paying it

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:26.080
as though we were leasing for
it, when we stop paying for it,

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:26.946
it could go away.

00:14:26.946 --> 00:14:28.570
So in fact, libraries
might in fact not

00:14:28.570 --> 00:14:31.430
have collections if we were
only turning from owners

00:14:31.430 --> 00:14:33.020
of the information
and the knowledge

00:14:33.020 --> 00:14:35.232
into those who are
leasing it, or renters.

00:14:35.232 --> 00:14:36.690
And many people
have worked on this

00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:38.190
from many different angles.

00:14:38.190 --> 00:14:40.970
Here, I would say, in the cradle
of the open access movement.

00:14:40.970 --> 00:14:44.000
That is one great answer
to it, where at the FAS

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.477
level and Bob Darnton and
others led the effort there,

00:14:46.477 --> 00:14:48.060
and at Harvard Law
School, where we've

00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:50.555
committed to putting our
materials in the commons

00:14:50.555 --> 00:14:51.740
in an open access way.

00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:53.230
That's not such a big deal.

00:14:53.230 --> 00:14:56.810
But for the vast majority of
what is created and published,

00:14:56.810 --> 00:14:59.390
we actually have potentially
a less good arrangement

00:14:59.390 --> 00:15:02.970
going forward if we don't
change the deal that is being

00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:05.260
offered for digital materials.

00:15:05.260 --> 00:15:08.020
Just out of curiosity, if
you were reading something,

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:12.410
how many people still prefer
this, a hard-copy kind of book?

00:15:12.410 --> 00:15:13.400
Vast majority.

00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:16.780
How many people prefer an ebook?

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:17.700
Relatively few.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:19.660
And how many people are
more or less agnostic,

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:21.750
you kind of do both?

00:15:21.750 --> 00:15:22.550
Interesting.

00:15:22.550 --> 00:15:24.666
I think that may be the
growing group actually,

00:15:24.666 --> 00:15:26.290
is those who want to
read this at night

00:15:26.290 --> 00:15:27.373
but carry this on a plane.

00:15:27.373 --> 00:15:29.445
I think that's kind
of the growth of it.

00:15:29.445 --> 00:15:31.570
Oh, Stuart Schieber, also
the open access champion.

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:33.460
I'm sorry, I didn't you
see you there before.

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:35.430
Congratulations and thank you.

00:15:35.430 --> 00:15:37.690
But the basic
point being that we

00:15:37.690 --> 00:15:39.320
need to ensure that
in a digital age

00:15:39.320 --> 00:15:42.250
there is just as much access
from a democratic perspective

00:15:42.250 --> 00:15:45.050
as there's been, if not more so.

00:15:45.050 --> 00:15:47.959
So this picture shows
a moment in time

00:15:47.959 --> 00:15:50.000
when we were actually
building that Boston Public

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.580
Library, when we were putting
up this amazing edifice

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:54.020
in the middle of Copley Square.

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:56.240
It was a few decades
after the library started.

00:15:56.240 --> 00:15:58.070
It was 1890.

00:15:58.070 --> 00:15:59.900
And the reason I
love this picture is

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:02.260
because I think that's,
roughly speaking, the moment

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:03.550
we find ourselves in now.

00:16:03.550 --> 00:16:06.480
We have a moment where we
are building for the future

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:08.316
the next set of libraries.

00:16:08.316 --> 00:16:09.690
And it is a set
of libraries that

00:16:09.690 --> 00:16:12.730
will exist both in digital
form and in physical form.

00:16:12.730 --> 00:16:15.390
And I think we actually ought
to be thinking about this

00:16:15.390 --> 00:16:17.130
in architectural form.

00:16:17.130 --> 00:16:19.610
So does anybody
recognize this one?

00:16:19.610 --> 00:16:22.280
A lot of people work
in this building.

00:16:22.280 --> 00:16:25.410
This is a side elevation
of Langdell Hall.

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:29.510
And it is to my mind the
moment that we're in right now,

00:16:29.510 --> 00:16:31.382
which is where we are
convening together,

00:16:31.382 --> 00:16:33.590
I think-- or ought to be
convening-- those people who

00:16:33.590 --> 00:16:36.600
think about information
architecture and the importance

00:16:36.600 --> 00:16:39.040
of the digital era
and how we actually

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:40.870
frame and make
accessible information

00:16:40.870 --> 00:16:42.940
with the analog era.

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:45.700
I think that future will
be a hybrid of libraries

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:48.190
that are very much physical
spaces, but also which

00:16:48.190 --> 00:16:50.890
connect to the cyberspace
that we are creating.

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:53.340
And I think in order to do
that well, what we need to do

00:16:53.340 --> 00:16:55.684
is actually convene all
of these people together

00:16:55.684 --> 00:16:58.100
and actually work in a way
that is much more collaborative

00:16:58.100 --> 00:17:00.305
than we've done in the past.

00:17:00.305 --> 00:17:02.305
One of the ways in which
we've been doing that--

00:17:02.305 --> 00:17:05.860
and many people in this
room are to thank for that;

00:17:05.860 --> 00:17:10.329
Bob Darnton called together a
group of 40 people at Radcliffe

00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:13.960
Institute a few years ago
to convene an effort really

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:17.109
to say, can we in fact
come up with the design

00:17:17.109 --> 00:17:21.099
for a combined public
and private effort

00:17:21.099 --> 00:17:24.130
to create a combined
hybrid digital

00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:25.630
and physical infrastructure?

00:17:25.630 --> 00:17:28.440
That has become the idea
behind the Digital Public

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:29.770
Library of America.

00:17:29.770 --> 00:17:32.890
40 people in that room actually
agreed to this sentence,

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:34.580
"To create an open
distributed network

00:17:34.580 --> 00:17:36.930
of comprehensive
online resources."

00:17:36.930 --> 00:17:39.130
And that's sort of a
crazy ambitious thing

00:17:39.130 --> 00:17:42.272
that nobody thought in fact
could work, but somehow it has.

00:17:42.272 --> 00:17:43.730
And Rebecca Haycock
and many people

00:17:43.730 --> 00:17:45.270
here have made it come together.

00:17:45.270 --> 00:17:47.150
I think it's one
example of what we

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:50.440
can do to solve this problem.

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:52.640
OK, so pause there
for a second and say,

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:55.690
what are the elements of
a library in a digital age

00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:58.750
that the Digital Public Library
of America and other things

00:17:58.750 --> 00:18:01.100
might be able to bring about?

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:04.430
I think fundamentally,
libraries remain about people.

00:18:04.430 --> 00:18:07.600
So I think that the
crucial aspect of libraries

00:18:07.600 --> 00:18:11.890
is keeping the humanity
in the transaction

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:14.540
between people and information,
people and knowledge.

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:17.219
I think one of the challenges
that people often throw out

00:18:17.219 --> 00:18:19.760
about libraries is we don't need
them so much, because people

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:23.250
can help themselves so easily
through these kinds of devices.

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:25.330
One example of
this that struck me

00:18:25.330 --> 00:18:28.320
as I was writing a book about
the importance of librarians

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:31.030
happened in a small-town
library in Andover, Mass.

00:18:31.030 --> 00:18:33.332
I was editing one chapter
and it was about 3:00

00:18:33.332 --> 00:18:34.040
in the afternoon.

00:18:34.040 --> 00:18:36.384
A whole pile of kids came
in after school, which

00:18:36.384 --> 00:18:37.550
is a fun thing that happens.

00:18:37.550 --> 00:18:40.065
Libraries fill up with
students who are spilling out

00:18:40.065 --> 00:18:41.640
of schools when they close.

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:44.182
And the kids all went into the
teen section, and some of them

00:18:44.182 --> 00:18:46.598
were doing their homework and
others were gaming and doing

00:18:46.598 --> 00:18:47.300
other things.

00:18:47.300 --> 00:18:50.090
And one of them was trying
to do a science thing.

00:18:50.090 --> 00:18:52.540
And the kid turned to
his iPhone he said,

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:55.010
Siri, what does
terminal velocity mean?

00:18:55.010 --> 00:18:56.690
This was in the
middle of a library.

00:18:56.690 --> 00:18:58.690
And Siri, it turned
out, did not know

00:18:58.690 --> 00:19:00.096
what terminal velocity meant.

00:19:00.096 --> 00:19:00.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:00.810 --> 00:19:03.430
But like three feet away
was an amazing librarian.

00:19:03.430 --> 00:19:06.730
And I was sure that that woman
could have either told him

00:19:06.730 --> 00:19:09.489
exactly what terminal velocity
meant or at least shown him--

00:19:09.489 --> 00:19:11.030
probably better--
the way to find out

00:19:11.030 --> 00:19:12.660
about terminal velocity.

00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:15.070
You see these examples
over and over again,

00:19:15.070 --> 00:19:16.570
but I think it is
important to note.

00:19:16.570 --> 00:19:19.080
And this is one of the
aspects of this book that

00:19:19.080 --> 00:19:20.280
is a little challenging.

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:22.040
There is a tough-love
story here,

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:23.780
which is when we
study young people

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:25.530
and how they look
for information,

00:19:25.530 --> 00:19:27.420
librarians are pretty
low on that list.

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:29.400
The project information
literacy studies

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:31.820
are probably the
clearest in that zone,

00:19:31.820 --> 00:19:34.276
that kids often do look
to Google and Wikipedia.

00:19:34.276 --> 00:19:35.650
They often look
to their teachers

00:19:35.650 --> 00:19:37.074
in that particular class.

00:19:37.074 --> 00:19:38.740
But we have to do a
better job, I think,

00:19:38.740 --> 00:19:41.180
as librarians and people who
work in libraries, to ensure

00:19:41.180 --> 00:19:43.370
that kids actually do go
and use these resources

00:19:43.370 --> 00:19:44.900
and know to do that,
and we actually

00:19:44.900 --> 00:19:47.500
have to prompt them to do it
and to teach them to do it.

00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:49.700
But I start with the
humanity as a key element

00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:52.490
of libraries in a digital age.

00:19:52.490 --> 00:19:55.020
Second, I think
libraries have to shift

00:19:55.020 --> 00:19:58.530
from being standalone silos--
which I think there have been

00:19:58.530 --> 00:20:01.140
lots of reasons for them
to be-- to being platforms

00:20:01.140 --> 00:20:03.160
and to being connected entities.

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:05.030
So this, I think,
invokes a lot of the work

00:20:05.030 --> 00:20:06.960
that Yochai has done in
the wealth of networks

00:20:06.960 --> 00:20:07.607
and otherwise.

00:20:07.607 --> 00:20:09.440
If you think about the
history of libraries,

00:20:09.440 --> 00:20:11.660
go back thousands of
years to the library

00:20:11.660 --> 00:20:13.160
at the Palace of
Ebla, for instance,

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:16.170
in modern day Syria, or
the Library of Alexandria--

00:20:16.170 --> 00:20:17.695
the idea behind the
library in a way

00:20:17.695 --> 00:20:19.150
was you brought
all that material.

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:20.733
Whatever you could
get, you brought it

00:20:20.733 --> 00:20:21.710
to a particular place.

00:20:21.710 --> 00:20:23.460
And now you may think
about it as bringing

00:20:23.460 --> 00:20:25.500
to a particular school,
a particular zip code,

00:20:25.500 --> 00:20:26.760
all of those materials.

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:29.215
And that was understandable
as a previous iteration

00:20:29.215 --> 00:20:30.450
of libraries.

00:20:30.450 --> 00:20:33.890
I still think to some extent
we do that, and too often

00:20:33.890 --> 00:20:36.655
I sometimes hear of schools
bragging about how many volumes

00:20:36.655 --> 00:20:38.780
they have or how much they
spend on their libraries

00:20:38.780 --> 00:20:40.660
in order to attract
kids or people.

00:20:40.660 --> 00:20:42.230
I think that misses the point.

00:20:42.230 --> 00:20:45.080
I think it misses the point
that by working much more

00:20:45.080 --> 00:20:47.200
together and actually
by seeing libraries

00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:49.010
as a connected
series of platforms,

00:20:49.010 --> 00:20:52.590
as part of the network, they
can accomplish much more.

00:20:52.590 --> 00:20:54.760
This particular
design of a platform

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:57.950
is the DPLA's rough
structure, the Digital Public

00:20:57.950 --> 00:20:59.400
Library of America.

00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:01.420
And the key to it,
in a way, is the fact

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:04.140
that it is just a whole
pile of open source

00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:08.280
code with a whole pile of
open metadata and as much open

00:21:08.280 --> 00:21:10.040
access material as
you possibly can have,

00:21:10.040 --> 00:21:11.520
and a bunch of
different parties.

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:13.230
In this case, service
hubs are states

00:21:13.230 --> 00:21:16.075
by and large, Content hubs are
things like Harvard University.

00:21:16.075 --> 00:21:17.700
Thank you, [? Sara ?]
Thomas and others

00:21:17.700 --> 00:21:20.110
for contributing material in.

00:21:20.110 --> 00:21:23.940
And the ability to export on
a bulk basis for anybody who

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:25.350
wishes to do it.

00:21:25.350 --> 00:21:28.490
And as you see from the
top, the notion that nobody

00:21:28.490 --> 00:21:30.090
has yet figured
out the right way

00:21:30.090 --> 00:21:33.250
to present library
material in a digital age.

00:21:33.250 --> 00:21:34.740
And the point is
that we can have

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:36.250
lots of potential frontends.

00:21:36.250 --> 00:21:38.650
We can have lots of different
applications and ways

00:21:38.650 --> 00:21:41.770
to share our materials,
especially if we think of them

00:21:41.770 --> 00:21:44.070
as platforms, pool the
materials together,

00:21:44.070 --> 00:21:49.950
and make it possible through
an open API, an ability

00:21:49.950 --> 00:21:53.810
to create any front-end
that you would like.

00:21:53.810 --> 00:21:57.480
So today there is one way
to get it, which is dp.la.

00:21:57.480 --> 00:22:00.370
You could go on your mobile
device or your computer,

00:22:00.370 --> 00:22:02.840
and you can find a
search engine and a way

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:04.320
into all of these materials.

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:06.010
But likewise, if you
go back a screen,

00:22:06.010 --> 00:22:08.520
that's just this
particular front-end.

00:22:08.520 --> 00:22:10.950
I think the ultimate
success of the project

00:22:10.950 --> 00:22:14.040
is that any library could
create on this open API

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:17.280
the ability to find a better
way to do this presentation,

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:19.410
to find a way to
present this material.

00:22:19.410 --> 00:22:22.370
And any library could create an
application or a front-end that

00:22:22.370 --> 00:22:24.670
would in fact make it
so that nobody even

00:22:24.670 --> 00:22:26.580
knew that the DPLA was there.

00:22:26.580 --> 00:22:30.140
The DPLA could be,
ultimately, entirely plumbing,

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:32.980
and the success be in the way
in which different communities

00:22:32.980 --> 00:22:34.569
have presented this material.

00:22:34.569 --> 00:22:36.860
That's a very different way
of thinking about libraries

00:22:36.860 --> 00:22:39.850
as institutions, but it's
about taking advantage

00:22:39.850 --> 00:22:41.890
of what the miracles
of the web have

00:22:41.890 --> 00:22:43.550
made possible and that magic.

00:22:43.550 --> 00:22:46.300
And that, I think, requires
us to be a little bit less

00:22:46.300 --> 00:22:48.680
egocentric as
institutions and much more

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:51.390
seeing it as a way to share.

00:22:51.390 --> 00:22:56.010
As of right now, just a small
plug for where the DPLA is.

00:22:56.010 --> 00:22:59.860
We have filled up about a third
of the map in terms of places

00:22:59.860 --> 00:23:02.350
contributing materials
into this Digital Public

00:23:02.350 --> 00:23:04.110
Library of America.

00:23:04.110 --> 00:23:07.800
The red states-- I
suppose that's maybe

00:23:07.800 --> 00:23:10.310
not the colors we should have
used for this in this room--

00:23:10.310 --> 00:23:12.820
are the ones that do have up
and running-- actually it's

00:23:12.820 --> 00:23:16.190
perfect, Harvard colors, in
that way-- have service hubs.

00:23:16.190 --> 00:23:17.700
So if you look at
Massachusetts, we

00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:19.337
have the Digital Commonwealth.

00:23:19.337 --> 00:23:21.670
And if you think about what
the Digital Commonwealth is,

00:23:21.670 --> 00:23:24.640
it's a fabulous example for
what the rest of the country

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:25.480
could do.

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:27.820
So at the Boston
Public Library there

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:30.590
are people like [? I, ?]
Tom Blake and a team,

00:23:30.590 --> 00:23:34.170
and what they do is they go out
to all the 351 cities and towns

00:23:34.170 --> 00:23:35.870
in the Commonwealth
of Massachusetts

00:23:35.870 --> 00:23:39.030
and help them digitize materials
and add metadata to it,

00:23:39.030 --> 00:23:41.940
and then share it up
through a statewide portal.

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:44.260
What the DPLA does is it
creates a way to share

00:23:44.260 --> 00:23:45.706
that on a national basis.

00:23:45.706 --> 00:23:47.080
So if you imagine,
if every state

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:49.380
had a Digital
Commonwealth equivalent,

00:23:49.380 --> 00:23:52.090
we would in fact be
building for the country

00:23:52.090 --> 00:23:54.600
an amazing series of
on-ramps into something

00:23:54.600 --> 00:23:55.860
that everybody could access.

00:23:55.860 --> 00:23:57.940
We're about a third
of the way there.

00:23:57.940 --> 00:23:59.940
Dan Cohen, who's the
current executive director,

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:03.307
and others are doing a fabulous
job of filling out this map.

00:24:03.307 --> 00:24:05.890
If you happen to come from any
of these states that do not yet

00:24:05.890 --> 00:24:08.920
have a DPLA hub and
you'd like to be one,

00:24:08.920 --> 00:24:11.959
let us know because we can
get you signed right up.

00:24:11.959 --> 00:24:13.750
The other thing that's
important to look at

00:24:13.750 --> 00:24:16.190
are these yellow ones,
the content hubs.

00:24:16.190 --> 00:24:18.230
Those are the big
institutions like Harvard

00:24:18.230 --> 00:24:21.770
and others-- bless you-- who
are in the process of digitizing

00:24:21.770 --> 00:24:25.020
tons of material and making them
available in this particular

00:24:25.020 --> 00:24:26.710
way to the rest of the country.

00:24:26.710 --> 00:24:30.067
And my hunch is, if we could
have every institution doing

00:24:30.067 --> 00:24:31.900
what the National Archive
is doing and doing

00:24:31.900 --> 00:24:34.274
what Smithsonian is doing and
New York Public and Harvard

00:24:34.274 --> 00:24:36.750
and so forth, we would
be creating potentially

00:24:36.750 --> 00:24:40.690
the most amazing library that
has ever existed in the world.

00:24:40.690 --> 00:24:44.040
And that, I think, is a
very exciting premise.

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:47.100
Much of it does come
from the work of people

00:24:47.100 --> 00:24:50.120
who are literally in this room.

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:51.800
This is the Oliver
Wendell Holmes suite,

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:53.550
which is all of those
materials, including

00:24:53.550 --> 00:24:55.090
that first image that I showed.

00:24:55.090 --> 00:24:57.650
And if you think about
these collections that

00:24:57.650 --> 00:24:59.750
once were called hidden
collections at Harvard--

00:24:59.750 --> 00:25:02.800
they were sort of hidden away in
different places-- I think even

00:25:02.800 --> 00:25:04.802
if we just put them
on the web and we

00:25:04.802 --> 00:25:06.260
have people come
find them, they're

00:25:06.260 --> 00:25:07.485
still a little bit hidden.

00:25:07.485 --> 00:25:09.590
And I think part of
the key to the step

00:25:09.590 --> 00:25:12.240
that we're taking right
now, and particularly

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:15.060
as we take amazing collections
like the Oliver Wendell Holmes

00:25:15.060 --> 00:25:17.880
collection and other ones that
are extremely well-curated

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:20.200
and shared, we can
make them unhidden

00:25:20.200 --> 00:25:23.370
in this same network model
by putting it in the DPLA.

00:25:23.370 --> 00:25:25.920
Now, of course, we should
caveat the problem of copyright.

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:27.770
We'll come back to that later.

00:25:27.770 --> 00:25:32.320
But subject to any licenses that
we have that we can share it,

00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:34.880
I think putting things
in this shared repository

00:25:34.880 --> 00:25:37.160
makes them much more valuable.

00:25:37.160 --> 00:25:39.820
Second, I think that by
doing it in this way,

00:25:39.820 --> 00:25:44.620
in an open way with an open
API as a chance for people

00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:47.790
to be able to do anything they
wish with the information,

00:25:47.790 --> 00:25:51.240
we'll be able to unleash
a whole lot of innovation.

00:25:51.240 --> 00:25:54.760
So this is an old schematic, but
one that came from the Harvard

00:25:54.760 --> 00:25:56.970
Library Innovation Lab.

00:26:00.090 --> 00:26:03.080
I'm going to give a
couple examples from that.

00:26:03.080 --> 00:26:05.970
You may think about libraries
and worry about some

00:26:05.970 --> 00:26:07.540
of the things we
would lose if we

00:26:07.540 --> 00:26:09.500
were to go in a digital
direction, which

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:10.670
we continue to.

00:26:10.670 --> 00:26:13.190
I think one of those fears
has been serendipity,

00:26:13.190 --> 00:26:15.597
the idea that if you do not
have physical libraries,

00:26:15.597 --> 00:26:16.930
you don't actually have a shelf.

00:26:16.930 --> 00:26:19.650
You don't have a place where
you can go and get a call number

00:26:19.650 --> 00:26:21.720
and walk in and find
a book you want,

00:26:21.720 --> 00:26:23.720
and then see all those
other amazing books that

00:26:23.720 --> 00:26:24.930
are to the right and
the left of them.

00:26:24.930 --> 00:26:26.320
And you probably all
have that experience

00:26:26.320 --> 00:26:28.153
of coming out with 10
books when you thought

00:26:28.153 --> 00:26:29.380
you were coming out with one.

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:30.963
And I think that's
one of those things

00:26:30.963 --> 00:26:32.490
that we don't want
to lose when we

00:26:32.490 --> 00:26:35.030
go from physical libraries
to whatever future

00:26:35.030 --> 00:26:36.400
we're going toward.

00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:38.794
My hunch is that
even if we contract

00:26:38.794 --> 00:26:41.210
those stacks a little bit--
and we shouldn't contract them

00:26:41.210 --> 00:26:42.626
anymore than we
already have, just

00:26:42.626 --> 00:26:46.290
to be clear-- we actually can
do some things that introduce

00:26:46.290 --> 00:26:47.580
new forms of serendipity.

00:26:47.580 --> 00:26:49.960
We actually might be
able, in a hybrid world,

00:26:49.960 --> 00:26:52.974
to do better than we have
done in just the analog.

00:26:52.974 --> 00:26:53.640
And why is that?

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:55.672
One reason, to take
the Harvard example--

00:26:55.672 --> 00:26:57.630
what is the current count
of Harvard libraries?

00:26:57.630 --> 00:26:59.220
Is it still in the 70s?

00:26:59.220 --> 00:26:59.769
73?

00:26:59.769 --> 00:27:00.310
AUDIENCE: 73.

00:27:00.310 --> 00:27:03.700
JOHN PALFREY: 73 distinct
libraries within a system.

00:27:03.700 --> 00:27:05.920
The fact of the matter
is, when you also

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:08.960
add in the depository
25 miles away,

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:10.910
there's actually no
stack at Harvard.

00:27:10.910 --> 00:27:12.460
There's no place
where you could walk

00:27:12.460 --> 00:27:15.860
in and see all the books, all
the collection, in the system.

00:27:15.860 --> 00:27:18.340
So if you could imagine
a world in which you

00:27:18.340 --> 00:27:20.810
have the stacks that are
fabulous ones in Widener

00:27:20.810 --> 00:27:23.900
and here and Langdell and so
forth as one place to walk in,

00:27:23.900 --> 00:27:28.000
but you also could combine all
the materials from all those 73

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
libraries, plus all the
materials in the Harvard

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.254
depository in a virtual sense,
and create a virtual stack,

00:27:33.254 --> 00:27:34.920
you could have new
forms of serendipity.

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:36.700
You could actually
find connections

00:27:36.700 --> 00:27:39.530
that were not previously
possible or findable.

00:27:39.530 --> 00:27:40.930
This was an example.

00:27:40.930 --> 00:27:42.960
Stack View was a
rendering, a way

00:27:42.960 --> 00:27:44.460
to put all of the
Harvard collection

00:27:44.460 --> 00:27:45.940
together, as you may know.

00:27:45.940 --> 00:27:48.950
This was based on
2009 circulation data,

00:27:48.950 --> 00:27:51.520
so circulation data
from a long time ago.

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:53.325
And the basic idea
was very simple.

00:27:53.325 --> 00:27:55.330
The idea was you
could then search

00:27:55.330 --> 00:27:59.142
on different forms of
metadata that people have

00:27:59.142 --> 00:28:00.350
added into their collections.

00:28:00.350 --> 00:28:01.895
So in this particular
case, someone

00:28:01.895 --> 00:28:04.000
is searching for
Gravity's Rainbow,

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:07.150
and they can see how many
times that particular book has

00:28:07.150 --> 00:28:08.799
circulated in a
certain period of time.

00:28:08.799 --> 00:28:11.090
But you also might see that
another book has circulated

00:28:11.090 --> 00:28:12.596
much more frequently.

00:28:12.596 --> 00:28:13.970
You could also
search, of course,

00:28:13.970 --> 00:28:16.090
if you're a graduate student,
how many of your professors

00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:17.970
have checked out this
version or another.

00:28:17.970 --> 00:28:19.594
You could imagine if
it were The Illiad

00:28:19.594 --> 00:28:21.640
and we had 40
examples of that, you

00:28:21.640 --> 00:28:24.050
might want to search on
which of those translations

00:28:24.050 --> 00:28:26.090
or which of those forwards
was most important.

00:28:26.090 --> 00:28:29.570
You could imagine ways in which
all of that great metadata that

00:28:29.570 --> 00:28:32.700
librarians have could become
more valuable if it were

00:28:32.700 --> 00:28:35.660
a combination of the digital
with the physical in somebody's

00:28:35.660 --> 00:28:36.160
hands.

00:28:36.160 --> 00:28:38.410
And I think that is the
possibility that lies ahead

00:28:38.410 --> 00:28:40.470
of us, and why this
research and development

00:28:40.470 --> 00:28:44.680
effort, particularly on top of
open systems, is so important.

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:47.440
I would add one other example
that I think is crucial.

00:28:47.440 --> 00:28:52.650
Also in the Harvard Library
innovation lab is perma.cc.

00:28:52.650 --> 00:28:55.070
For those who haven't followed
this particular effort,

00:28:55.070 --> 00:28:58.060
I think it's an
amazing example of why

00:28:58.060 --> 00:29:01.256
libraries have a crucial
role to play going forward.

00:29:01.256 --> 00:29:02.880
I've talked mostly
about the importance

00:29:02.880 --> 00:29:05.405
in a democratic society
of access to information,

00:29:05.405 --> 00:29:08.820
and I think that is really
the primary one for libraries.

00:29:08.820 --> 00:29:12.206
But I think preservation of
information and preservation

00:29:12.206 --> 00:29:13.580
of where the
information is found

00:29:13.580 --> 00:29:16.470
is equally important in
many respects for libraries.

00:29:16.470 --> 00:29:19.840
One thing I fear is that if
we don't actually think ahead

00:29:19.840 --> 00:29:21.950
to the kinds of
systems that we ought

00:29:21.950 --> 00:29:23.610
to have for the
long-term, we're going

00:29:23.610 --> 00:29:25.120
to make an enormous mistake.

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:27.970
I think perma.cc is
one example of how

00:29:27.970 --> 00:29:31.642
we can create permanent
forms of digital archiving,

00:29:31.642 --> 00:29:33.600
and where librarians
actually can lead in a way

00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:36.187
that we have not
one as much before.

00:29:36.187 --> 00:29:38.020
This is a project that
is currently ongoing.

00:29:38.020 --> 00:29:40.228
I know Jonathan and his
team-- we could talk about it

00:29:40.228 --> 00:29:42.800
afterwards, so I won't explain
it entirely, and leave you

00:29:42.800 --> 00:29:44.190
the chance to do it.

00:29:44.190 --> 00:29:46.690
But I think it's an example of
the amazing innovation that's

00:29:46.690 --> 00:29:49.080
happening in libraries, and
the importance of libraries

00:29:49.080 --> 00:29:50.460
playing this role.

00:29:50.460 --> 00:29:53.680
One of the challenges that we've
put out to libraries in general

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:55.500
is if you think about
in the information

00:29:55.500 --> 00:29:57.280
era in the last
several years, I don't

00:29:57.280 --> 00:29:58.840
think most of the
big innovations

00:29:58.840 --> 00:30:00.155
have actually come
out of libraries.

00:30:00.155 --> 00:30:01.700
So if you think
about search, that

00:30:01.700 --> 00:30:04.140
has come out of, obviously,
big companies like Google.

00:30:04.140 --> 00:30:05.690
If you think about
recommendations,

00:30:05.690 --> 00:30:07.770
by and large that has
come out of big companies

00:30:07.770 --> 00:30:09.725
like Amazon and Netflix, maybe.

00:30:09.725 --> 00:30:11.100
If you think about
encyclopedias,

00:30:11.100 --> 00:30:13.800
that came out of a
commodity trader's head,

00:30:13.800 --> 00:30:17.090
and a bunch of people are
collaborating in Wikipedia.

00:30:17.090 --> 00:30:18.440
Lots of other examples of it.

00:30:18.440 --> 00:30:20.064
But I actually think
libraries have not

00:30:20.064 --> 00:30:22.240
been on the forefront of
the very big innovations,

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:24.950
and I still think that lies
ahead as a possibility.

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:27.730
And with a series of open
systems and collaboration,

00:30:27.730 --> 00:30:31.420
I think that's entirely,
entirely possible.

00:30:31.420 --> 00:30:33.170
I'm about to bring it
in for a landing, so

00:30:33.170 --> 00:30:34.860
here's the windup to that.

00:30:34.860 --> 00:30:37.724
I think ultimately, the thing
that libraries need most to do

00:30:37.724 --> 00:30:39.390
and where I think
most of the excitement

00:30:39.390 --> 00:30:43.011
is actually solving a series of
problems that face communities.

00:30:43.011 --> 00:30:45.260
And as I go around the country
talking about this book

00:30:45.260 --> 00:30:48.760
or in the context of
DPLA, it's so clear

00:30:48.760 --> 00:30:50.940
that from many,
many perspectives,

00:30:50.940 --> 00:30:54.020
libraries have a crucial
role to play in communities.

00:30:54.020 --> 00:30:57.110
And that could be very simply,
providing access to kids

00:30:57.110 --> 00:30:59.570
after school when they don't
have another place to access

00:30:59.570 --> 00:31:01.403
information because
they actually don't have

00:31:01.403 --> 00:31:03.130
a broadband connection at home.

00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:05.682
You hear many kids getting
assigned kinds of homework

00:31:05.682 --> 00:31:07.640
that they actually can't
complete without being

00:31:07.640 --> 00:31:09.290
able to go to a library.

00:31:09.290 --> 00:31:12.850
And I heard from kids who at
6:00 when the library closed

00:31:12.850 --> 00:31:14.740
then had to go to
McDonald's or Starbucks,

00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:16.470
because that's where
the free Wi-Fi was.

00:31:16.470 --> 00:31:19.530
I think there's an enormously
powerful role in bridging

00:31:19.530 --> 00:31:22.130
this participation gap
and the digital divide

00:31:22.130 --> 00:31:23.380
from the library perspective.

00:31:23.380 --> 00:31:25.002
I think that's true
for job seekers.

00:31:25.002 --> 00:31:27.460
It's true for people who are
new immigrants to the country.

00:31:27.460 --> 00:31:29.650
I think it's true for
elderly people who come

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:31.350
to libraries as a social place.

00:31:31.350 --> 00:31:34.460
These are hugely important roles
that libraries continue to play

00:31:34.460 --> 00:31:36.300
outside of the scholarly realm.

00:31:36.300 --> 00:31:38.080
And I won't go through
all those examples,

00:31:38.080 --> 00:31:40.610
because everybody knows
them so well here.

00:31:40.610 --> 00:31:43.660
I think in the end we do need
libraries as physical spaces.

00:31:43.660 --> 00:31:46.884
Does anybody recognize
this library?

00:31:46.884 --> 00:31:48.290
AUDIENCE: The John
Adams Library?

00:31:48.290 --> 00:31:50.706
JOHN PALFREY: Yes, The John
Adams Library in Quincy, Mass.

00:31:50.706 --> 00:31:52.250
They're just such
amazing spaces that

00:31:52.250 --> 00:31:54.360
have been created in libraries.

00:31:54.360 --> 00:31:56.756
So my argument in
no way is to say

00:31:56.756 --> 00:31:58.380
that we shouldn't
have physical spaces,

00:31:58.380 --> 00:32:00.730
glorious physical spaces,
in our communities.

00:32:00.730 --> 00:32:02.730
I think libraries
play an essential role

00:32:02.730 --> 00:32:05.980
in creating third spaces
that are open and public.

00:32:05.980 --> 00:32:07.810
I just think that
people may come to them

00:32:07.810 --> 00:32:10.060
for different reasons, and
we may need to support them

00:32:10.060 --> 00:32:11.329
for very different reasons.

00:32:11.329 --> 00:32:13.120
One thing you see about
the Adams library--

00:32:13.120 --> 00:32:14.950
you can imagine at
this table that these

00:32:14.950 --> 00:32:16.320
were big reference tomes.

00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:18.092
I don't think people
are necessarily

00:32:18.092 --> 00:32:20.050
going to come to a library
for reference tomes.

00:32:20.050 --> 00:32:21.716
They're going to come
for other reasons.

00:32:21.716 --> 00:32:25.390
And I think part of our job is
to figure out what those are.

00:32:25.390 --> 00:32:27.740
I think we will continue
to have physical books.

00:32:27.740 --> 00:32:30.520
My argument is not in any
way that we won't actually

00:32:30.520 --> 00:32:33.780
have physical and beautiful
objects that present material.

00:32:33.780 --> 00:32:37.060
I'm not positive that the market
will be exactly as it is today.

00:32:37.060 --> 00:32:40.050
My sense is we will have very
beautiful physical objects

00:32:40.050 --> 00:32:44.480
and things that present in large
sizes and in beautiful formats,

00:32:44.480 --> 00:32:46.910
and we will have mostly
digital materials otherwise.

00:32:46.910 --> 00:32:48.860
I think things will be
mostly born digital.

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:52.010
I suspect that e-books will
press on that paperback

00:32:52.010 --> 00:32:54.440
market or the market of
less beautiful objects,

00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:56.250
but I think we still
do have a material

00:32:56.250 --> 00:32:57.660
culture that people like.

00:32:57.660 --> 00:33:00.770
And even kids seem to continue
like those physical objects,

00:33:00.770 --> 00:33:02.270
so I don't think
they're going away.

00:33:02.270 --> 00:33:03.810
But we do have to
figure out a way--

00:33:03.810 --> 00:33:06.520
how do we support libraries
when patrons hold up

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:09.250
their hands just the way
you did in this room, many

00:33:09.250 --> 00:33:12.440
saying I prefer the paper, some
saying you prefer the digital.

00:33:12.440 --> 00:33:15.110
And with a trend toward
increasingly digital, one

00:33:15.110 --> 00:33:17.410
of the things that
we have put libraries

00:33:17.410 --> 00:33:19.317
in such a tough
position with is saying,

00:33:19.317 --> 00:33:21.150
with the same amount
of money or less money,

00:33:21.150 --> 00:33:23.780
you have to do both the digital
stuff and the physical stuff.

00:33:23.780 --> 00:33:25.539
That is an untenable position.

00:33:25.539 --> 00:33:27.330
We've got to figure
out a way, whether it's

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:28.860
through collaboration
or continuing

00:33:28.860 --> 00:33:32.920
to support through funding
or it's capital investment,

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:34.960
to allow libraries
to be able to thrive

00:33:34.960 --> 00:33:37.620
in what is going to be
both physical and digital

00:33:37.620 --> 00:33:39.340
as a world.

00:33:39.340 --> 00:33:41.885
I think we should do it in a
global context, to be sure.

00:33:41.885 --> 00:33:45.320
And this was one of the parts
of Bob's genius and others

00:33:45.320 --> 00:33:47.370
as we started out with
the Digital Public

00:33:47.370 --> 00:33:48.730
Library of America.

00:33:48.730 --> 00:33:51.190
Yes, of course, it's been
seen as a national effort,

00:33:51.190 --> 00:33:53.200
but it's been done in an
international context.

00:33:53.200 --> 00:33:55.760
The United States is actually
not the first country

00:33:55.760 --> 00:33:59.515
to come up with a digital
strategy for their nation.

00:33:59.515 --> 00:34:02.350
The Europeans actually are
much further ahead, at least

00:34:02.350 --> 00:34:05.430
time-wise, in the form of
Europeana, as an example.

00:34:05.430 --> 00:34:07.910
And very much the first
thing that DPLA did

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:11.800
was to find a way to
work with the Europeans.

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:13.600
And the notion was
not to say, we're

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:16.130
just going to create one
worldwide library or one

00:34:16.130 --> 00:34:18.550
worldwide digital
library of Alexandria,

00:34:18.550 --> 00:34:21.419
but to say we can actually have
maybe 200 different countries

00:34:21.419 --> 00:34:23.960
having theirs, but figure out
how to make them interoperable.

00:34:23.960 --> 00:34:25.790
How do you ensure
that from the user

00:34:25.790 --> 00:34:28.710
perspective people actually
can access these materials?

00:34:28.710 --> 00:34:30.630
So one of the first
things DPLA did

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:33.299
was to create an
exhibit on immigration

00:34:33.299 --> 00:34:35.090
that showed people
going from the old world

00:34:35.090 --> 00:34:36.790
to the new and the
new world to the old,

00:34:36.790 --> 00:34:39.370
to ensure that as we built
this system it would actually

00:34:39.370 --> 00:34:40.594
work on a global level.

00:34:40.594 --> 00:34:42.260
We have the diversity
and the difference

00:34:42.260 --> 00:34:44.843
and the innovation that happens
in all these different country

00:34:44.843 --> 00:34:48.416
levels, but we actually
connect it in a global vision.

00:34:48.416 --> 00:34:50.889
And in some ways
most importantly,

00:34:50.889 --> 00:34:52.739
I put up here a map of Utopia.

00:34:52.739 --> 00:34:54.480
You can see it here.

00:34:54.480 --> 00:34:57.350
My view is we should
dream really, really big.

00:34:57.350 --> 00:34:59.810
This is the moment
when we are designing

00:34:59.810 --> 00:35:02.890
what public libraries and
scholarly libraries and school

00:35:02.890 --> 00:35:05.700
libraries can and should
be for the future.

00:35:05.700 --> 00:35:08.730
And I am not so pollyannish
to say that we are absolutely

00:35:08.730 --> 00:35:10.040
going to become a utopia.

00:35:10.040 --> 00:35:10.916
That's not the point.

00:35:10.916 --> 00:35:13.331
But the point is we should
have something that we actually

00:35:13.331 --> 00:35:14.565
are building toward in mind.

00:35:14.565 --> 00:35:16.190
It should be a shared
vision that we're

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:17.260
really excited about.

00:35:17.260 --> 00:35:20.160
And I feel like that's
entirely, entirely possible,

00:35:20.160 --> 00:35:23.130
to put that vision ahead of us
and to build as much toward it

00:35:23.130 --> 00:35:25.130
as we can, and to
say that we are not

00:35:25.130 --> 00:35:29.130
going to accept a digital
world or a digital hybrid

00:35:29.130 --> 00:35:32.270
with the physical world that's
actually less good than what

00:35:32.270 --> 00:35:34.050
we've had in the past
in terms of access,

00:35:34.050 --> 00:35:36.460
in terms of preservation,
in terms of commitment

00:35:36.460 --> 00:35:38.100
to democratic ideals.

00:35:38.100 --> 00:35:40.810
And I think that it's an
extremely exciting moment

00:35:40.810 --> 00:35:41.970
to come together.

00:35:41.970 --> 00:35:43.812
So I hope very
much that you will

00:35:43.812 --> 00:35:45.020
share your questions with me.

00:35:45.020 --> 00:35:47.630
But most importantly,
thank you for being

00:35:47.630 --> 00:35:49.880
engaged in a discussion about
the future of libraries.

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:51.460
And I look forward to
working with all of you

00:35:51.460 --> 00:35:52.639
to make it very bright.

00:35:52.639 --> 00:35:53.637
Thank you so much.

