think the first thing that

00:38:54.850 --> 00:38:56.300
should happen is that the
President should invite

00:38:56.300 --> 00:38:58.196
you to take up that
post in a few months

00:38:58.196 --> 00:39:02.110
now that you're available,
which I think would be fun.

00:39:02.110 --> 00:39:03.570
I think the next
person should do

00:39:03.570 --> 00:39:06.100
a couple things that I think
the Library of Congress

00:39:06.100 --> 00:39:07.660
has not done.

00:39:07.660 --> 00:39:10.750
One is, in a fundamental
way, to see itself

00:39:10.750 --> 00:39:12.714
as a national library.

00:39:12.714 --> 00:39:14.880
And I think the Library of
Congress in some respects

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:17.772
has dodged that for a long
time, by saying in part

00:39:17.772 --> 00:39:19.230
it's a research
arm of the Congress

00:39:19.230 --> 00:39:21.310
and in part it's our national
library, but not quite.

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:22.810
I think you have
to grab it and say,

00:39:22.810 --> 00:39:25.890
this is the national library,
and we are not the whole thing

00:39:25.890 --> 00:39:27.587
but we are connected
to the rest of it,

00:39:27.587 --> 00:39:29.420
and should actually
play nice with the rest.

00:39:29.420 --> 00:39:33.760
And to say that there in fact
is a really positive role

00:39:33.760 --> 00:39:36.847
that the Library of Congress
can play in an interconnected

00:39:36.847 --> 00:39:37.680
and networked world.

00:39:37.680 --> 00:39:39.060
I think that would be one.

00:39:39.060 --> 00:39:40.602
I think two would
be then-- so that's

00:39:40.602 --> 00:39:42.643
sort of a conceptual shift,
but an important one.

00:39:42.643 --> 00:39:44.740
And two would be to take
on mass digitization

00:39:44.740 --> 00:39:45.990
in a meaningful way.

00:39:45.990 --> 00:39:47.390
So I think that
people have often

00:39:47.390 --> 00:39:49.100
pointed to the World
Digital Library

00:39:49.100 --> 00:39:51.760
and the 11,000 or so objects
that have been digitized it it.

00:39:51.760 --> 00:39:55.290
That's too small a number,
I think, for internet scale.

00:39:55.290 --> 00:39:58.770
And I think for an entity
like the Library of Congress

00:39:58.770 --> 00:40:01.420
to take up this job
of mass digitilization

00:40:01.420 --> 00:40:03.410
and to work with the
National Archives, which

00:40:03.410 --> 00:40:07.100
has been hard at work at it,
the Smithsonian, the GPO, lots

00:40:07.100 --> 00:40:08.587
of other parties
in the government,

00:40:08.587 --> 00:40:10.670
and actually lead that
effort-- I think that could

00:40:10.670 --> 00:40:11.990
be enormously powerful.

00:40:11.990 --> 00:40:14.480
A third thing would
be join the DPLA.

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:16.270
So one of the
absurdities, I think,

00:40:16.270 --> 00:40:18.670
of the process we've
had for five years

00:40:18.670 --> 00:40:20.550
is that we have the
National Archives,

00:40:20.550 --> 00:40:22.520
we have the Smithsonian,
we have the GPO,

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:24.900
we have lots of other federal
agencies participating.

00:40:24.900 --> 00:40:26.720
And yet, the Library
of Congress has

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:30.610
resisted our invitations for
all that time, which seems to me

00:40:30.610 --> 00:40:31.490
bizarre.

00:40:31.490 --> 00:40:32.920
