that spread out
1,600 communities

00:42:24.970 --> 00:42:27.430
wide in the early 20th century.

00:42:27.430 --> 00:42:29.420
So I think they should
be publicly financed,

00:42:29.420 --> 00:42:30.260
by and large.

00:42:30.260 --> 00:42:32.680
I do think that philanthropy
has a huge role to play,

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:34.680
and one of the arguments
that I make in the book

00:42:34.680 --> 00:42:37.720
is to say that, at moments
of key transition--

00:42:37.720 --> 00:42:39.170
as Mr. Carnegie
did; and there are

00:42:39.170 --> 00:42:41.430
lots of reasons to
criticize Carnegie,

00:42:41.430 --> 00:42:43.430
but one thing he did was
he put a lot of capital

00:42:43.430 --> 00:42:46.490
into libraries that spread
them from big cities

00:42:46.490 --> 00:42:48.510
into lots of small towns
at a crucial moment.

00:42:48.510 --> 00:42:49.990
So I actually
think it'd be great

00:42:49.990 --> 00:42:51.870
if the Carnegie Corporation
or the MacArthur

00:42:51.870 --> 00:42:54.036
Foundation or others would
in fact stand up and say,

00:42:54.036 --> 00:42:57.750
this is a moment to do a
big investment of that sort.

00:42:57.750 --> 00:43:00.750
After that, I think one of
the questions is to say,

00:43:00.750 --> 00:43:02.320
should libraries
be in the business

00:43:02.320 --> 00:43:04.180
of selling stuff
or having a revenue

00:43:04.180 --> 00:43:07.200
model that looks otherwise?

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:09.660
I think that libraries,
archives, museums,

00:43:09.660 --> 00:43:12.315
are all asking these
kinds of questions.

00:43:12.315 --> 00:43:14.690
There are, of course, things
that we can license and make

00:43:14.690 --> 00:43:15.700
some money on.

00:43:15.700 --> 00:43:18.430
This library here, of course,
has made some amount of money

00:43:18.430 --> 00:43:21.890
on royalties by virtue of
taking materials we had

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:24.860
and digitizing those, allowing
people then to sell them back

00:43:24.860 --> 00:43:26.360
to us or other libraries.

00:43:26.360 --> 00:43:28.309
I think there's
something in that.

00:43:28.309 --> 00:43:30.350
But I would much rather
see a business model that

00:43:30.350 --> 00:43:32.551
was focused on
collaboration, and one

00:43:32.551 --> 00:43:34.550
that was focused on open
access and other things

00:43:34.550 --> 00:43:36.600
that I actually think we
have the seeds of here,

00:43:36.600 --> 00:43:38.010
rather than see it
as something where

00:43:38.010 --> 00:43:40.430
we actually have to have a
corporate-style business model.

00:43:40.430 --> 00:43:42.770
But others may disagree.

00:43:42.770 --> 00:43:46.510
Second of the three questions,
about legal changes--

00:43:46.510 --> 00:43:49.380
I think just to
state it really fast,

00:43:49.380 --> 00:43:51.270
Orphan Works legislation
should change.

00:43:51.270 --> 00:43:53.310
So to Bob's question,
one of the great things

00:43:53.310 --> 00:43:55.930
about the Library of Congress
is that position overseas,

00:43:55.930 --> 00:43:57.422
the Register of Copyrights.

00:43:57.422 --> 00:43:59.130
So the Library of
Congress could stand up

00:43:59.130 --> 00:44:01.460
and say, look,
really simply, nobody

00:44:01.460 --> 00:44:04.890
is hurt by having Orphan Works
legislation-- tens of millions

00:44:04.890 --> 00:44:07.080
of works that could be
made available that are not

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:07.990
being made available.

00:44:07.990 --> 00:44:10.694
And if somebody finds that
they're the copyright holder,

00:44:10.694 --> 00:44:12.860
they then will be able to
put it back into copyright

00:44:12.860 --> 00:44:14.730
if they wish to, or not.

00:44:14.730 --> 00:44:17.210
And in fact, I just can't see
how Orphan Works legislation

00:44:17.210 --> 00:44:18.930
doesn't really help everyone.

00:44:18.930 --> 00:44:21.300
Section 108 reform--
there are special rules

00:44:21.300 --> 00:44:22.370
that relate to libraries.

00:44:22.370 --> 00:44:24.910
There are special rules that
allow libraries to do things,

00:44:24.910 --> 00:44:27.640
for instance, for those who
have different abilities-- so

00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:28.880
for the blind and otherwise.

00:44:28.880 --> 00:44:31.730
There are specific rules that
are way out of date and ought

00:44:31.730 --> 00:44:32.650
to be reformed.

00:44:32.650 --> 00:44:35.176
So we've gone a certain
distance on Section 108 reform.

00:44:35.176 --> 00:44:36.550
We could go further
and so forth.

00:44:36.550 --> 00:44:38.500
So there are a series
of things, I think,

00:44:38.500 --> 00:44:39.980
in that area that are crucial.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:41.510
And the other piece
of legal reform

00:44:41.510 --> 00:44:44.340
that needs to be tied to
that is privacy reform.

00:44:44.340 --> 00:44:46.810
I think libraries have
done such a great job

00:44:46.810 --> 00:44:50.160
of being the places where
we protect reader privacy.

00:44:50.160 --> 00:44:52.670
We need to ensure that
the law allows libraries

00:44:52.670 --> 00:44:54.520
to do that on an ongoing basis.

00:44:54.520 --> 00:44:56.397
And last, makerspaces--
yes, for sure.

00:44:56.397 --> 00:44:58.480
One of the things you
pushed me to do when I first

00:44:58.480 --> 00:45:02.160
took this job was to focus
on co-production, the idea

00:45:02.160 --> 00:45:04.410
that libraries are spaces
in which we are producing

00:45:04.410 --> 00:45:05.910
new knowledge of various sorts.

00:45:05.910 --> 00:45:07.280
Makerspaces are one example.

00:45:07.280 --> 00:45:09.885
The new media labs popping up
around the country are another.

00:45:09.885 --> 00:45:12.170
I think they're great
examples of bringing people

00:45:12.170 --> 00:45:14.070
into libraries to
create new knowledge.

00:45:14.070 --> 00:45:16.660
I feel like that's the
excitement of having

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:19.010
an open application
programming interface layer,

00:45:19.010 --> 00:45:21.689
and so forth, which is
in-person and from afar

00:45:21.689 --> 00:45:23.730
we can create new things
that have never existed.

00:45:26.740 --> 00:45:27.450
Yeah?

00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:28.540
AUDIENCE: Hi, John.

00:45:28.540 --> 00:45:32.670
Pat McCormick, former
student, Kennedy School grad.

00:45:32.670 --> 00:45:33.990
I can't wait to read the book.

00:45:33.990 --> 00:45:36.136
So excuse me if
this is in the book.

00:45:36.136 --> 00:45:38.196
JOHN PALFREY: No
problem. [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:38.196 --> 00:45:39.070
one way or the other.

00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:41.250
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:45:41.250 --> 00:45:45.600
I'm very interested in the API
and the platform and all that,

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:47.829
but my question is more mundane.

00:45:47.829 --> 00:45:49.370
In the city where
I live, Somerville,

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:53.620
we're struggling to keep library
branches open, to restore them,

00:45:53.620 --> 00:45:56.390
to create new spaces
that aren't traditional.

00:45:56.390 --> 00:45:59.160
And it seems like
this concept would

00:45:59.160 --> 00:46:04.436
allow us to open a library with
fewer books-- assuming we have

00:46:04.436 --> 00:46:06.060
the platform as well;
that's not to say

00:46:06.060 --> 00:46:09.060
we don't need the books--
in different spaces

00:46:09.060 --> 00:46:12.210
to restore historic
buildings and reuse them

00:46:12.210 --> 00:46:13.322
in different ways.

00:46:13.322 --> 00:46:14.780
And I was just
wondering the extent

00:46:14.780 --> 00:46:16.730
to which you've
thought about this

00:46:16.730 --> 00:46:20.460
as a way of creating more
flexibility, lower cost

00:46:20.460 --> 00:46:23.492
barriers for physical
libraries in our cities.

00:46:23.492 --> 00:46:25.075
JOHN PALFREY: That's
a great question.

00:46:25.075 --> 00:46:27.470
And I understand Somerville
has a fabulous new librarian.

00:46:27.470 --> 00:46:29.290
You've got-- it's
an exciting moment

00:46:29.290 --> 00:46:31.850
for Somerville in particular.

00:46:31.850 --> 00:46:35.250
So my preferred answer was
that we fund libraries fully,

00:46:35.250 --> 00:46:38.140
and that they have a fabulous
physical infrastructure

00:46:38.140 --> 00:46:39.310
and branches that are open.

00:46:39.310 --> 00:46:41.726
Actually, one of the things
that Boston Public Library did

00:46:41.726 --> 00:46:43.630
was introduce the branch
system, as well-- so

00:46:43.630 --> 00:46:45.610
have lots of
community-based libraries,

00:46:45.610 --> 00:46:47.120
and support them well.

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:50.400
I think the reality is that
we don't in communities often

00:46:50.400 --> 00:46:52.190
make that full investment.

00:46:52.190 --> 00:46:55.260
And I think that's where we
have to say, so what can we do?

00:46:55.260 --> 00:46:58.000
How do we embrace this future
while also doing as much

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.340
of the fabulous existing
stuff as we can?

00:47:00.340 --> 00:47:02.800
I think the only answer
there is to collaborate,

00:47:02.800 --> 00:47:04.910
is to say that we
don't need to bring

00:47:04.910 --> 00:47:07.886
the same collection to every
one of these physical spaces.

00:47:07.886 --> 00:47:10.510
Librarians, of course, have done
this very well for a long time

00:47:10.510 --> 00:47:12.218
with interlibrary loan
and with a variety

00:47:12.218 --> 00:47:14.020
of other forms of
sharing, but I think

00:47:14.020 --> 00:47:17.680
those can be amped up and
done more extensively.

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:20.650
And of course, as
I've argued, I think

00:47:20.650 --> 00:47:22.840
from a digital
perspective, every library

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:24.721
should not be creating
its own iPad app.

00:47:24.721 --> 00:47:26.220
Not every library
should be creating

00:47:26.220 --> 00:47:28.910
its own various digital systems.

00:47:28.910 --> 00:47:30.630
That is something
that we can, if we

00:47:30.630 --> 00:47:33.980
take a page enough out of
the open source movement,

00:47:33.980 --> 00:47:35.120
do in a collaborative way.

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:38.310
And I think that would
allow for communities

00:47:38.310 --> 00:47:41.850
to make choices as to how they
spend what are scarcer dollars.

00:47:41.850 --> 00:47:45.510
So would I rather see
fewer books in libraries?

00:47:45.510 --> 00:47:46.140
Of course not.

00:47:46.140 --> 00:47:48.280
But I think where we have
to make that choice--

00:47:48.280 --> 00:47:49.950
do as much collaboration
as possible

00:47:49.950 --> 00:47:51.450
to allow as much
choice as possible.

00:47:51.450 --> 00:47:52.658
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Over here.

00:47:52.658 --> 00:47:53.890
Did the mic find a new home?

00:48:02.160 --> 00:48:03.910
AUDIENCE: Hi, my name
is Ron [? Newman. ?]

00:48:03.910 --> 00:48:07.170
I've been using libraries
for about 54 years.

00:48:07.170 --> 00:48:12.280
I wanted to come back to that
slide and what it represents.

00:48:12.280 --> 00:48:13.290
It's very seductive.

00:48:13.290 --> 00:48:17.700
On the other hand, it also shows
a limitation of physical stacks

00:48:17.700 --> 00:48:19.970
as they are now, which is
that a book, as it comes

00:48:19.970 --> 00:48:22.670
into the library, gets one
Dewey decimal or Library

00:48:22.670 --> 00:48:25.850
of Congress number and
forever that's the one

00:48:25.850 --> 00:48:26.820
place where it is.

00:48:26.820 --> 00:48:28.500
In a digital system
you can do better

00:48:28.500 --> 00:48:30.460
than that, because
that book can sit

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:32.760
on many different shelf lists.

00:48:32.760 --> 00:48:35.470
Is there opportunity
for some sort of wiki

00:48:35.470 --> 00:48:40.100
kind of cataloging system
to emerge from this so

00:48:40.100 --> 00:48:43.740
that many people can
collectively catalog material

00:48:43.740 --> 00:48:45.819
better than one person can?

00:48:45.819 --> 00:48:47.610
JOHN PALFREY: There's
some people laughing.

00:48:47.610 --> 00:48:49.720
Tracy, do you want that one?

00:48:49.720 --> 00:48:50.220
No?

00:48:50.220 --> 00:48:51.910
Tracy does not wish it.

00:48:51.910 --> 00:48:52.680
Anyone else?

00:48:52.680 --> 00:48:54.234
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:54.234 --> 00:48:55.400
JOHN PALFREY: Yeah, exactly.

00:48:55.400 --> 00:48:57.450
So if somebody in the Harvard
Library System liked it--

00:48:57.450 --> 00:48:58.460
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: It
would be fitting to have

00:48:58.460 --> 00:48:59.490
the answer crowdsourced.

00:48:59.490 --> 00:49:00.990
JOHN PALFREY: Yeah,
that's exactly--

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:03.681
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:06.050 --> 00:49:07.770
AUDIENCE: I certainly
think that we

00:49:07.770 --> 00:49:10.700
have catalog systems that do
allow different kinds of access

00:49:10.700 --> 00:49:11.200
points.

00:49:11.200 --> 00:49:15.550
And they may not be as
seductive and as appealing

00:49:15.550 --> 00:49:17.650
as this kind of
display, but they

00:49:17.650 --> 00:49:22.710
are initial and in some ways
rudimentary attempts to combine

00:49:22.710 --> 00:49:24.920
digital information and
physical information

00:49:24.920 --> 00:49:28.100
into a wide variety of indexes
that give the user lots

00:49:28.100 --> 00:49:29.260
of ways to get into it.

00:49:29.260 --> 00:49:31.820
The problem is they're
a little too complex.

00:49:31.820 --> 00:49:33.380
And so we still
need to keep working

00:49:33.380 --> 00:49:35.630
at figuring out how
to make it both simple

00:49:35.630 --> 00:49:36.950
but complex at the same time.

00:49:39.734 --> 00:49:42.150
JOHN PALFREY: My answer-- Tracy
knows vastly more about it

00:49:42.150 --> 00:49:44.700
than I do, and from a
technical perspective

00:49:44.700 --> 00:49:46.610
there are a zillion
challenges behind it.

00:49:46.610 --> 00:49:49.460
But I think from a conceptual
perspective, the idea

00:49:49.460 --> 00:49:53.150
that there's one indicator for
something in an old-school way,

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:55.860
as compared to saying you could
have many more data points that

00:49:55.860 --> 00:49:58.610
allow different ways into it, I
think that conceptual shift is

00:49:58.610 --> 00:50:00.470
actually very, very important.

00:50:00.470 --> 00:50:04.260
And I think the trend,
which is moving away

00:50:04.260 --> 00:50:07.470
from having the knowledge
be in a particular catalog

00:50:07.470 --> 00:50:10.730
or a particular catalog entry
to one where in fact there

00:50:10.730 --> 00:50:13.975
are many more ways to
identify the information

00:50:13.975 --> 00:50:17.168
and then do more with it, is
sort of an obvious movement.

00:50:20.734 --> 00:50:22.650
MARCY MURNINGHAM: My
name is Marcy Murningham,

00:50:22.650 --> 00:50:26.660
and my question
pertains to the theme

00:50:26.660 --> 00:50:29.430
of hybrid and collaboration.

00:50:29.430 --> 00:50:33.520
There are vast pools of
financial assets swimming

00:50:33.520 --> 00:50:37.720
around every community,
billions and billions of dollars

00:50:37.720 --> 00:50:41.040
in the form of assets
under management

00:50:41.040 --> 00:50:45.230
for tax-exempt
institutional investors.

00:50:45.230 --> 00:50:49.750
In theory, those
tax-exempt institutions

00:50:49.750 --> 00:50:52.330
exist to advance
the public interest.

00:50:52.330 --> 00:50:55.350
That is the reason for
their tax-exempt status.

00:50:55.350 --> 00:50:59.640
And Boston, as we know, is
very rich in those kinds

00:50:59.640 --> 00:51:01.830
of institutions.

00:51:01.830 --> 00:51:06.870
According to my research, the
top 60 tax-exempt institutions

00:51:06.870 --> 00:51:12.195
in Boston have combined
assets of over $50 billion.

00:51:12.195 --> 00:51:15.650
There are ways, it
seems to me, for tapping

00:51:15.650 --> 00:51:19.630
into some of that
money and bending it

00:51:19.630 --> 00:51:23.860
toward the public
interest-- that is to say,

00:51:23.860 --> 00:51:27.940
institutions such as
public libraries that

00:51:27.940 --> 00:51:30.660
otherwise rely on
taxpayer revenue streams

00:51:30.660 --> 00:51:31.820
or even philanthropy.

00:51:31.820 --> 00:51:34.630
I'd just encourage you
to think more creatively

00:51:34.630 --> 00:51:40.280
about revenue sources that
could be bent toward libraries

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:42.025
in our nation's communities.

00:51:42.025 --> 00:51:42.360
JOHN PALFREY: Thank you.

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:43.651
I think that's very thoughtful.

00:51:43.651 --> 00:51:46.150
I would imagine that one
of those is this one,

00:51:46.150 --> 00:51:48.560
is Harvard and others.

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:52.440
Also one school that has
a fair amount of capital,

00:51:52.440 --> 00:51:54.160
not the same amount
that this one does,

00:51:54.160 --> 00:51:56.570
but I think that's
important to note.

00:51:56.570 --> 00:51:59.000
I think one of the
reasons why I think

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:01.310
it's incumbent upon
this institution

00:52:01.310 --> 00:52:03.200
to do things like open
access, to do things

00:52:03.200 --> 00:52:06.880
like digitize its materials
and share them more broadly,

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:09.190
even though there's not
a revenue stream back

00:52:09.190 --> 00:52:10.767
to this institution,
is because I

00:52:10.767 --> 00:52:12.350
think we are private
institutions that

00:52:12.350 --> 00:52:13.670
have a public purpose.

00:52:13.670 --> 00:52:15.760
And I think if we don't
see it that way we're

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:17.460
making a huge mistake.

00:52:17.460 --> 00:52:20.624
Whether or not there would be
a tax on these institutions

00:52:20.624 --> 00:52:22.290
that then goes back
to public libraries,

00:52:22.290 --> 00:52:25.200
I'm not sure that that's
necessarily right either.

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:27.290
But I think that it's a
very interesting question,

00:52:27.290 --> 00:52:29.920
and I think it's one that
we have to figure out

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:31.910
how we are justifying,
in a sense,

00:52:31.910 --> 00:52:34.300
holding this amount of
capital in a relatively

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:37.570
small number of institutions.

00:52:37.570 --> 00:52:38.778
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Over here?

00:52:42.152 --> 00:52:42.860
ERICA CHARIS: Hi.

00:52:42.860 --> 00:52:45.460
My name's Erica Charis,
and I'm a librarian over

00:52:45.460 --> 00:52:46.626
at Berklee College of Music.

00:52:46.626 --> 00:52:48.774
JOHN PALFREY: Awesome.

00:52:48.774 --> 00:52:50.815
AUDIENCE: The ideas that
are something in my head

00:52:50.815 --> 00:52:54.600
that I'm hoping to hear
what your thoughts are on,

00:52:54.600 --> 00:52:57.140
if libraries are about
people and libraries

00:52:57.140 --> 00:52:58.780
are becoming more
digital, how do

00:52:58.780 --> 00:53:00.790
we bridge the gap
between the kid talking

00:53:00.790 --> 00:53:04.130
into his phone and the
librarian sitting at the desk

00:53:04.130 --> 00:53:05.260
three feet away?

00:53:05.260 --> 00:53:08.377
What does digital service
necessarily look like?

00:53:08.377 --> 00:53:09.960
JOHN PALFREY: That's
a great question.

00:53:09.960 --> 00:53:11.350
I suspect many
people in the room

00:53:11.350 --> 00:53:14.290
have great thoughts
and answers to this.

00:53:14.290 --> 00:53:16.510
I think part of it is
actually as teachers

00:53:16.510 --> 00:53:19.080
that we actually have
to tell that student

00:53:19.080 --> 00:53:20.440
to go talk to that person.

00:53:20.440 --> 00:53:24.050
We need to make that
human connection happen.

00:53:24.050 --> 00:53:26.250
I've been teaching United
States history this year

00:53:26.250 --> 00:53:29.354
to a group of 14 kids who
are in their junior year

00:53:29.354 --> 00:53:31.520
of high school, and I think
one of the things you do

00:53:31.520 --> 00:53:34.760
is assign kids to go
talk to a librarian,

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:36.620
and to have them
interface therefore

00:53:36.620 --> 00:53:39.830
with all these amazing
things as part of a paper.

00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:43.377
And I think that kind of thing
that many professors do here

00:53:43.377 --> 00:53:44.960
at the law school
[INAUDIBLE] actually

00:53:44.960 --> 00:53:47.230
say, in the course of working on
something you actually must go

00:53:47.230 --> 00:53:48.420
spend time with the librarian.

00:53:48.420 --> 00:53:50.670
I think that's actually a
really positive thing to do,

00:53:50.670 --> 00:53:53.370
and I think it creates
connections and pathways that

00:53:53.370 --> 00:53:56.220
are essential and
actually breaks down

00:53:56.220 --> 00:53:58.380
what is happening, when
in the digital world

00:53:58.380 --> 00:53:59.297
we sometimes withdraw.

00:53:59.297 --> 00:54:00.880
Even though we think
it's more social,

00:54:00.880 --> 00:54:04.674
sometimes we're withdrawing,
away from human contact.

00:54:04.674 --> 00:54:06.090
So I actually
think, as educators,

00:54:06.090 --> 00:54:08.190
in some sense we have
to construct ways

00:54:08.190 --> 00:54:09.695
to bring people back together.

00:54:09.695 --> 00:54:12.344
Now, could it be-- go ahead.

00:54:12.344 --> 00:54:13.260
I would love to hear--

00:54:13.260 --> 00:54:14.580
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: I think
you might be about to say

00:54:14.580 --> 00:54:15.650
what I'm going to ask you.

00:54:15.650 --> 00:54:18.040
JOHN PALFREY: So why don't you
say what was on my mind, yes?

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:19.914
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN:
Suppose Apple comes to you

00:54:19.914 --> 00:54:21.380
with a proposal for your advice.

00:54:21.380 --> 00:54:22.720
And Apple says, you know what?

00:54:22.720 --> 00:54:24.690
We'd like to improve
the Siri experience.

00:54:27.660 --> 00:54:29.400
The easiest part of
Siri is to answer

00:54:29.400 --> 00:54:34.077
the 20% of possible questions
that 80% of the people

00:54:34.077 --> 00:54:35.910
ask, which is like,
what's the weather going

00:54:35.910 --> 00:54:37.170
to be tomorrow or--

00:54:37.170 --> 00:54:38.500
JOHN PALFREY: What's the
score on the Red Sox game?

00:54:38.500 --> 00:54:39.625
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Exactly.

00:54:39.625 --> 00:54:40.860
Or, I'd like to buy a book.

00:54:40.860 --> 00:54:41.860
Maybe that won't happen.

00:54:41.860 --> 00:54:45.540
But anyway, there's a
bunch of other questions

00:54:45.540 --> 00:54:47.890
that are long-tail questions.

00:54:47.890 --> 00:54:51.220
What if the way that we
used to route letters

00:54:51.220 --> 00:54:55.250
that children wrote to Santa and
addressed to the North Pole--

00:54:55.250 --> 00:54:56.754
and they got sent
somewhere, right?

00:54:56.754 --> 00:54:57.670
I think they still do.

00:54:57.670 --> 00:55:00.550
They go to people who
answer the letters?

00:55:00.550 --> 00:55:02.300
I don't know what the
liability policy is.

00:55:02.300 --> 00:55:06.970
But what if similar
to that, we simply

00:55:06.970 --> 00:55:10.240
arranged for people
asking Siri to route

00:55:10.240 --> 00:55:14.270
those two reference librarians
around the country or the world

00:55:14.270 --> 00:55:17.540
who would then answer
through the Siri pipeline

00:55:17.540 --> 00:55:18.710
and be attributed to it.

00:55:18.710 --> 00:55:21.310
By the way, this is brought
to you courtesy of a library.

00:55:21.310 --> 00:55:23.751
And if you'd like to be more
about it, blah, blah, blah.

00:55:23.751 --> 00:55:25.250
What would your
reaction be to that?

00:55:25.250 --> 00:55:26.190
Is that like, no, no.

00:55:26.190 --> 00:55:28.190
That's exactly the kind
of corporate mediated

00:55:28.190 --> 00:55:30.015
dehumanization that
I rail against.

00:55:30.015 --> 00:55:31.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:31.390 --> 00:55:34.000
Or would it be, this
is exactly the kind

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:36.770
of public-private partnership
that would put libraries back

00:55:36.770 --> 00:55:39.860
at the center of the meaningful
questions people ask?

00:55:39.860 --> 00:55:42.620
JOHN PALFREY: So I will answer
that if I can ask my friend

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:45.490
Yochai to answer after I
do, because he's much more

00:55:45.490 --> 00:55:46.890
about that kind of system--

00:55:46.890 --> 00:55:49.098
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Yochai
is playing the role of Siri

00:55:49.098 --> 00:55:49.944
in this.

00:55:49.944 --> 00:55:52.110
JOHN PALFREY: This is the
advanced cold call request

00:55:52.110 --> 00:55:53.730
to my friend in a moment.

00:55:53.730 --> 00:55:56.063
I was really interested-- did
you see The New York Times

00:55:56.063 --> 00:55:58.010
article about is
Wikipedia in trouble

00:55:58.010 --> 00:55:59.943
as the numbers are
declining and so forth?

00:55:59.943 --> 00:56:02.170
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: They run
that article about every year.

00:56:02.170 --> 00:56:03.820
JOHN PALFREY: They do, but
it was in the Sunday Review

00:56:03.820 --> 00:56:04.240
this week.

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:05.864
We're seeing a little
bit more serious.

00:56:05.864 --> 00:56:08.850
It wasn't a great
article, but anyway.

00:56:08.850 --> 00:56:10.980
So here are a couple of answers.

00:56:10.980 --> 00:56:13.370
I would be hesitant to do that
particular deal with Apple

00:56:13.370 --> 00:56:14.744
for the reason
you're suggesting,

00:56:14.744 --> 00:56:21.180
which is I worry that
if what we keep doing

00:56:21.180 --> 00:56:23.850
is creating systems
that do not have

00:56:23.850 --> 00:56:25.845
the library as the
primary interface,

00:56:25.845 --> 00:56:27.970
whether it's a public
library or a research library

00:56:27.970 --> 00:56:31.530
or a special library or a school
library, I am troubled by that.

00:56:31.530 --> 00:56:35.065
So the deal with Apple makes
me nervous for a really, really

00:56:35.065 --> 00:56:35.690
simple reason--

00:56:35.690 --> 00:56:38.177
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: So the
model is free to all, so long

00:56:38.177 --> 00:56:39.510
as you come through our doorway.

00:56:39.510 --> 00:56:41.567
JOHN PALFREY: Right.

00:56:41.567 --> 00:56:43.150
Well, so long as you
don't necessarily

00:56:43.150 --> 00:56:44.983
have to come through
Apple's doorway, right?

00:56:44.983 --> 00:56:48.099
So if it were done in a
truly open source way,

00:56:48.099 --> 00:56:49.890
I could imagine that
being very attractive.

00:56:49.890 --> 00:56:51.970
If it's only
through Siri or it's

00:56:51.970 --> 00:56:53.727
creating a system
that relies upon Siri

00:56:53.727 --> 00:56:56.310
and the iPhone as opposed to an
Android device or [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:56.310 --> 00:56:57.810
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN:
You could imagine

00:56:57.810 --> 00:57:00.040
it building into the DPLA
as part of that stack

00:57:00.040 --> 00:57:02.520
and have an API call
to ask a librarian,

00:57:02.520 --> 00:57:05.650
and Siri can plug in, and
Google Now can plug in.

00:57:05.650 --> 00:57:08.260
JOHN PALFREY: That would be
much more interesting, for sure.

00:57:08.260 --> 00:57:10.460
But I wouldn't do a deal--
and I just think of Apple

00:57:10.460 --> 00:57:13.070
as the ultimate in
exclusive-- somebody

00:57:13.070 --> 00:57:16.310
has written about
this too, as have you.

00:57:16.310 --> 00:57:21.670
So yes, but only according to a
structure that was truly open.

00:57:21.670 --> 00:57:23.800
One thing that we've talked
a lot about with DPLA

00:57:23.800 --> 00:57:26.240
that's a fun idea
which is like this

00:57:26.240 --> 00:57:28.370
is the idea of the scannebago.

00:57:28.370 --> 00:57:30.530
I don't know if people
have heard this idea,

00:57:30.530 --> 00:57:32.367
but it's called the scannebago.

00:57:32.367 --> 00:57:33.450
I did not come up with it.

00:57:33.450 --> 00:57:35.140
Emily Gore who
works at DPLA did.

00:57:35.140 --> 00:57:36.080
But the idea of the scannebago--

00:57:36.080 --> 00:57:37.164
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN:
He's making Emily Gore

00:57:37.164 --> 00:57:39.030
be the recipient of the
trademark infringement letter.

00:57:39.030 --> 00:57:39.910
JOHN PALFREY: No, no.

00:57:39.910 --> 00:57:43.180
The idea of the scannebago
would be to get a Winnebago

00:57:43.180 --> 00:57:45.330
and put in the back
of it a scanner

00:57:45.330 --> 00:57:48.600
and drive it around the country
and have people bring out

00:57:48.600 --> 00:57:50.355
the materials that
they have to scan them,

00:57:50.355 --> 00:57:51.980
and then the people
who were driving it

00:57:51.980 --> 00:57:55.160
would help put in the
metadata and do the scanning.

00:57:55.160 --> 00:57:57.590
And you could imagine the
documentary or the NPR piece

00:57:57.590 --> 00:57:59.630
sort of writes
itself, this notion

00:57:59.630 --> 00:58:01.440
of driving around the country.

00:58:01.440 --> 00:58:05.950
And you could imagine it tapping
into library students, people

00:58:05.950 --> 00:58:08.160
who just care about libraries,
the sort of Wikipedia

00:58:08.160 --> 00:58:08.960
equivalents.

00:58:08.960 --> 00:58:11.760
You could see it also really
appealing to retired librarians

00:58:11.760 --> 00:58:15.930
as something that people could
do as part of this network.

00:58:15.930 --> 00:58:18.619
And I actually think about
when reference librarians

00:58:18.619 --> 00:58:20.285
retire, what are some
of the things that

00:58:20.285 --> 00:58:21.368
would be really fun to do?

00:58:21.368 --> 00:58:25.440
It might be occasionally to be
in this particular role, which

00:58:25.440 --> 00:58:27.110
I think the DPLA
actually could mediate

00:58:27.110 --> 00:58:28.360
in a really interesting way.

00:58:28.360 --> 00:58:30.300
So I think there is
a version of what

00:58:30.300 --> 00:58:34.110
has made Wikipedia so successful
that we could do for libraries.

00:58:34.110 --> 00:58:35.590
It'd be really,
really fun frankly.

00:58:35.590 --> 00:58:38.190
You think about Wikimania
coming to a place

00:58:38.190 --> 00:58:40.170
like this, as it did
a bunch of years ago.

00:58:40.170 --> 00:58:42.800
Having DPLA Fest be a place
where people showed up

00:58:42.800 --> 00:58:45.027
and actually edited metadata
and answered questions.

00:58:45.027 --> 00:58:45.860
It would be really--

00:58:45.860 --> 00:58:48.190
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: It's like
a collective Antiques Roadshow

00:58:48.190 --> 00:58:48.490
content.

00:58:48.490 --> 00:58:50.050
JOHN PALFREY: Yes, incredibly
geeky and incredibly fun.

00:58:50.050 --> 00:58:50.140
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN:
But there'd be

00:58:50.140 --> 00:58:52.290
a triage area at
the beginning to see

00:58:52.290 --> 00:58:53.670
if there's a copyright problem.

00:58:53.670 --> 00:58:54.980
JOHN PALFREY: Well,
there could be that, too.

00:58:54.980 --> 00:58:55.370
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: You'd
turn away a lot of stuff.

00:58:55.370 --> 00:58:56.142
JOHN PALFREY: That
could be true, too.

00:58:56.142 --> 00:58:58.270
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: These
Hardy Boys are too young.

00:58:58.270 --> 00:59:00.330
JOHN PALFREY: [INAUDIBLE]
risk with respect

00:59:00.330 --> 00:59:03.215
to the copyright, which would
be an interesting conversation.

00:59:03.215 --> 00:59:04.480
Y

00:59:04.480 --> 00:59:07.315
JOHN PALFREY: Are
you willing to--

00:59:07.315 --> 00:59:10.150
YOCHAI BENKLER: Jet lag
from being away for awhile

00:59:10.150 --> 00:59:12.800
notwithstanding, I'll try.

00:59:12.800 --> 00:59:15.620
Something that came out in the
exchange between the two of you

00:59:15.620 --> 00:59:20.490
and the scannebago
is let's not talk

00:59:20.490 --> 00:59:23.900
about the corporate
culture of Apple and Siri.

00:59:23.900 --> 00:59:26.822
Let's talk about the
isolation of the interaction

00:59:26.822 --> 00:59:27.530
with the machine.

00:59:27.530 --> 00:59:29.750
And you had said
something earlier

00:59:29.750 --> 00:59:35.310
about the human
experience of the library.

00:59:35.310 --> 00:59:39.170
You talked about
the kids coming.

00:59:39.170 --> 00:59:41.200
And as you start to talk
about the scannebago

00:59:41.200 --> 00:59:44.050
and who would come
and who wouldn't come,

00:59:44.050 --> 00:59:50.470
I'd love to hear more from you
about what the human platform

00:59:50.470 --> 00:59:54.790
element is, which is quite
distinct from the DPLA

00:59:54.790 --> 00:59:56.930
platform, is much
more like that,

00:59:56.930 --> 01:00:00.280
and is a form of a response to
the Siri question that's about.

01:00:00.280 --> 01:00:03.210
Even if it were fine from
the corporate perspective,

01:00:03.210 --> 01:00:06.420
it takes the service
aspect of the library

01:00:06.420 --> 01:00:11.530
and makes it available
to isolated individuals.

01:00:11.530 --> 01:00:13.710
And the question is, can
you say a little bit more,

01:00:13.710 --> 01:00:16.001
either from the book or your
experience with how you're

01:00:16.001 --> 01:00:19.880
thinking about building
the library at your school,

01:00:19.880 --> 01:00:25.260
about what it is that we do to
support that human interaction

01:00:25.260 --> 01:00:28.080
that libraries
traditionally have provided,

01:00:28.080 --> 01:00:30.540
and how that
connects, if at all,

01:00:30.540 --> 01:00:35.640
to this very powerful response
you began with Martha's

01:00:35.640 --> 01:00:39.550
question of, don't
need a business model,

01:00:39.550 --> 01:00:42.410
you need a story about the
core of the public service

01:00:42.410 --> 01:00:44.240
and about the core
of human interaction?

01:00:44.240 --> 01:00:46.449
Can you put a little bit
more flesh on those bones?

01:00:46.449 --> 01:00:48.740
JOHN PALFREY: So this is what
happens when you hang out

01:00:48.740 --> 01:00:50.174
with your old professors.

01:00:50.174 --> 01:00:52.340
They answer your question
with a hard question back.

01:00:52.340 --> 01:00:54.720
I totally didn't miss that
that's what just happened.

01:00:54.720 --> 01:00:57.840
I was hoping to glean some of
the brilliance of Yochai in it,

01:00:57.840 --> 01:00:59.600
but we got it in
a different form.

01:00:59.600 --> 01:01:00.920
So thank you.

01:01:00.920 --> 01:01:04.580
So the hard question, I
think, is an important one.

01:01:04.580 --> 01:01:07.060
So step one, from
my perspective,

01:01:07.060 --> 01:01:09.195
is the notion of
humanity, which is

01:01:09.195 --> 01:01:12.480
I actually think that
if we lose the notion

01:01:12.480 --> 01:01:15.910
of the incredible, incredible
group of people who work

01:01:15.910 --> 01:01:18.312
in libraries-- this is where
the love letter starts--

01:01:18.312 --> 01:01:20.645
and the experience of somebody
walking in-- whether it's

01:01:20.645 --> 01:01:23.490
a scholar or it's a kid or it's
an old person, whatever it is--

01:01:23.490 --> 01:01:25.570
that is a hugely
important, I think,

01:01:25.570 --> 01:01:28.330
democratic interaction
that actually doesn't have

01:01:28.330 --> 01:01:29.699
to do with the transaction.

01:01:29.699 --> 01:01:31.990
It doesn't have to do with
the transaction in the sense

01:01:31.990 --> 01:01:34.240
of Netflix wants you to think
about this movie instead

01:01:34.240 --> 01:01:34.980
of this movie.

01:01:34.980 --> 01:01:37.810
It has to do with
people in a community

01:01:37.810 --> 01:01:40.270
supporting one another and
doing what is civic work.

01:01:40.270 --> 01:01:42.950
So there's something that's
just essential about that.

01:01:42.950 --> 01:01:45.660
And no matter how quickly we
hurtle towards the digital,

01:01:45.660 --> 01:01:47.470
I want to be sure
that that humanity is

01:01:47.470 --> 01:01:49.230
in the mix in a
really fundamental way

01:01:49.230 --> 01:01:50.313
and that we don't lose it.

01:01:50.313 --> 01:01:52.740
So that is really,
really crucial to it.

01:01:52.740 --> 01:01:55.470
Your question, though, also
goes to what is the role

01:01:55.470 --> 01:01:57.070
of the librarian going forward.

01:01:57.070 --> 01:01:59.310
I would say in the
tough love category

01:01:59.310 --> 01:02:01.950
in this book is actually
saying to my friends who

01:02:01.950 --> 01:02:03.860
work in libraries and
others that I actually

01:02:03.860 --> 01:02:06.630
think the shift we have to
make is to see librarians

01:02:06.630 --> 01:02:09.540
as not necessarily working
for a single institution

01:02:09.540 --> 01:02:14.492
so much as working in the public
grid in a networked way, right?

01:02:14.492 --> 01:02:16.283
So there are about
100,000 school libraries

01:02:16.283 --> 01:02:17.158
in the United States.

01:02:17.158 --> 01:02:19.800
There are, call it,
15,000 public libraries

01:02:19.800 --> 01:02:22.140
and call it another 10,000
or 15,000 other kinds

01:02:22.140 --> 01:02:22.920
of libraries.

01:02:22.920 --> 01:02:24.970
So we're talking about
more than 100,000,

01:02:24.970 --> 01:02:26.990
but not 150,000, institutions.

01:02:26.990 --> 01:02:29.330
To the extent that each
of these institutions

01:02:29.330 --> 01:02:31.872
had some percentage--
if it's one person

01:02:31.872 --> 01:02:33.580
or it's a percentage
of somebody's time--

01:02:33.580 --> 01:02:37.240
which is really devoted to this
network public effort, I think,

01:02:37.240 --> 01:02:41.040
would be vastly more powerful
than as isolated institutions.

01:02:41.040 --> 01:02:42.260
And I realize that's a shift.

01:02:42.260 --> 01:02:43.920
That would be
saying to the dean,

01:02:43.920 --> 01:02:47.370
you're paying for people to
be focused on your professor,

01:02:47.370 --> 01:02:50.100
supporting the professor writing
this great book on cooperation

01:02:50.100 --> 01:02:51.683
or whatever it might
be-- you actually

01:02:51.683 --> 01:02:53.620
have to divert a certain
percentage of that

01:02:53.620 --> 01:02:54.970
to something that
is the public good.

01:02:54.970 --> 01:02:56.590
And by the way, it
will boomerang back

01:02:56.590 --> 01:02:57.820
in really awesome ways.

01:02:57.820 --> 01:02:59.440
And actually, this
is a bad example

01:02:59.440 --> 01:03:01.898
because I think this dean has
made exactly that enlightened

01:03:01.898 --> 01:03:03.790
decision at Harvard Law School.

01:03:03.790 --> 01:03:07.340
But I think if every library
were seeing itself in that way,

01:03:07.340 --> 01:03:08.840
I think that could
be very powerful.

01:03:08.840 --> 01:03:10.420
I think there are lots of
librarians in this room who

01:03:10.420 --> 01:03:12.250
actually lived that experience.

01:03:12.250 --> 01:03:15.680
But I'm not positive that that's
exactly what every institution

01:03:15.680 --> 01:03:18.560
sees itself as doing as every
town library, every school

01:03:18.560 --> 01:03:19.600
library, and so forth.

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:21.870
But I think that
networked approach

01:03:21.870 --> 01:03:23.690
could be enormously
powerful in ways

01:03:23.690 --> 01:03:25.560
that we haven't yet experienced.

01:03:25.560 --> 01:03:27.830
And I feel like it's taking
some of the learning that

01:03:27.830 --> 01:03:29.760
has made the exposure
on the web so exciting

01:03:29.760 --> 01:03:32.010
and the kinds of things that
have developed from that,

01:03:32.010 --> 01:03:33.900
and having that
apply in the library

01:03:33.900 --> 01:03:36.080
space for all these
amazing principles all

01:03:36.080 --> 01:03:38.210
this amazing
material that I think

01:03:38.210 --> 01:03:40.355
is so exciting for
what could come.

