You did a little riff on
what we'd call the first sale

01:04:06.230 --> 01:04:11.930
doctrine that says the anchor,
the platform of that library,

01:04:11.930 --> 01:04:14.029
for hundreds of years
has been the idea

01:04:14.029 --> 01:04:15.820
that once you've got
the physical artifact,

01:04:15.820 --> 01:04:18.450
you can lend it to someone
else, which also became

01:04:18.450 --> 01:04:19.950
the anchor of the
physical community

01:04:19.950 --> 01:04:22.580
because you had to go to the
library to fetch the book.

01:04:22.580 --> 01:04:26.030
So much of just that
lending is part of it.

01:04:26.030 --> 01:04:30.520
And you pointed out that
a bizarre paradox, but not

01:04:30.520 --> 01:04:34.500
a necessary one, about
digital advancements

01:04:34.500 --> 01:04:37.740
is, congratulations, now we have
a way of locking this stuff up

01:04:37.740 --> 01:04:43.000
tight where I might have a
privilege if I could figure out

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:47.300
how to unlock it, but I can't
figure it out and unlocking it

01:04:47.300 --> 01:04:49.360
itself may break the law.

01:04:49.360 --> 01:04:51.200
So that seems like one
snake in the garden.

01:04:51.200 --> 01:04:54.620
I just wanted to see, if
you follow the dotted line,

01:04:54.620 --> 01:04:57.230
do we end up with more
and more stuff locked up

01:04:57.230 --> 01:05:00.500
as fewer and fewer of these get
produced, because the economics

01:05:00.500 --> 01:05:01.930
are just so simple?

01:05:01.930 --> 01:05:05.160
You also said at the end, these
might be interesting artifacts,

01:05:05.160 --> 01:05:07.420
but they're not going to be
mass-produced the way they

01:05:07.420 --> 01:05:09.400
are even still today.

01:05:09.400 --> 01:05:15.920
And the second snake in the
garden is how you find stuff,

01:05:15.920 --> 01:05:18.170
that previously the
way to find stuff

01:05:18.170 --> 01:05:21.900
was through categorizations
done by librarians

01:05:21.900 --> 01:05:24.880
who had professional ethics
and responsibilities about how

01:05:24.880 --> 01:05:26.990
to order stuff and
truly try to make

01:05:26.990 --> 01:05:30.560
it accessible without wondering
about who paid them for product

01:05:30.560 --> 01:05:32.580
placement on the shelf?

01:05:32.580 --> 01:05:35.760
And now, as you say,
again and again we're

01:05:35.760 --> 01:05:39.380
going to Google, one in
a handful of companies,

01:05:39.380 --> 01:05:42.000
for all information,
not just monographs.

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:47.140
Follow that dotted line out,
and do you see any difference

01:05:47.140 --> 01:05:50.650
from the trend that's
already kind of overcome us

01:05:50.650 --> 01:05:55.060
of not going to the library
or the library system

01:05:55.060 --> 01:05:57.100
for that kind of categorization?

01:05:57.100 --> 01:06:00.300
Those two snakes in the garden,
if that's what they are--

01:06:00.300 --> 01:06:01.430
what do you do about them?

01:06:01.430 --> 01:06:03.674
JOHN PALFREY: I think that
is a very good summation,

01:06:03.674 --> 01:06:05.590
and maybe that's where
we should end so people

01:06:05.590 --> 01:06:06.900
can go do something else.

01:06:06.900 --> 01:06:08.090
But I think--

01:06:08.090 --> 01:06:09.420
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: They're
going to [INAUDIBLE] next door

01:06:09.420 --> 01:06:09.820
while eating.

01:06:09.820 --> 01:06:11.445
JOHN PALFREY: I'm so
glad. [INAUDIBLE].

01:06:11.445 --> 01:06:14.341
That's good, since this is
a celebration of libraries.

01:06:14.341 --> 01:06:14.840
No.

01:06:14.840 --> 01:06:16.560
I think those two
snakes in the grass,

01:06:16.560 --> 01:06:20.010
as they went their way
through, are huge risks.

01:06:20.010 --> 01:06:22.859
We didn't talk about the entire
mass of the rest of copyright

01:06:22.859 --> 01:06:24.400
and the difficulty
of doing something

01:06:24.400 --> 01:06:27.770
like DPLA given the
strictures of copyright,

01:06:27.770 --> 01:06:30.670
so I think that's more like
an elephant in the room

01:06:30.670 --> 01:06:32.260
than a snake in the grass.

01:06:32.260 --> 01:06:33.580
It's so obvious.

01:06:33.580 --> 01:06:35.450
But I think these
two, the notion

01:06:35.450 --> 01:06:39.560
of the absence of a
digital first sale doctrine

01:06:39.560 --> 01:06:42.030
and the requirement that
libraries increasingly

01:06:42.030 --> 01:06:45.390
become leasers as opposed
to owners-- when you combine

01:06:45.390 --> 01:06:47.610
that with the sort of
general corporatization--

01:06:47.610 --> 01:06:49.610
this is something that
goes back to the earliest

01:06:49.610 --> 01:06:51.490
days of the internet, and
what James Boyle and Yochai

01:06:51.490 --> 01:06:53.790
and others who are writing
about the enclosure movement.

01:06:53.790 --> 01:06:55.620
I think those are things,
those are lessons,

01:06:55.620 --> 01:06:57.786
that we've learned in other
parts of our scholarship

01:06:57.786 --> 01:07:00.210
that we have to apply over
here in the world of libraries,

01:07:00.210 --> 01:07:03.580
and actually seek to
bend the arc of where

01:07:03.580 --> 01:07:05.580
the future will go,
or the future that

01:07:05.580 --> 01:07:07.170
will be history will go.

01:07:07.170 --> 01:07:09.460
I think that's a really,
really important thing for us

01:07:09.460 --> 01:07:12.290
to stand up and say, we
don't want that version

01:07:12.290 --> 01:07:14.210
of what the future could hold.

01:07:14.210 --> 01:07:16.140
And one of the reasons
we don't want that

01:07:16.140 --> 01:07:18.070
is because I think it
will undermine support

01:07:18.070 --> 01:07:18.990
for libraries.

01:07:18.990 --> 01:07:20.570
And I think if we undermine
support for libraries

01:07:20.570 --> 01:07:22.150
and we don't support them
in the way that we should,

01:07:22.150 --> 01:07:23.470
I think that will
undermine our democracy

01:07:23.470 --> 01:07:26.120
and I think it will undermine
scholarship, which of course,

01:07:26.120 --> 01:07:27.820
are not unrelated also.

01:07:27.820 --> 01:07:30.140
And so yes, I think
those two snakes

01:07:30.140 --> 01:07:32.242
making their way through
the grass are worrisome.

01:07:32.242 --> 01:07:34.450
I don't know how to meld
the elephant stomping around

01:07:34.450 --> 01:07:35.889
with snakes.

01:07:35.889 --> 01:07:37.680
You're better at these
metaphors than I am.

01:07:37.680 --> 01:07:38.880
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: No, I was
just thinking of a Mark Twain

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:40.690
quote, that everybody always
talks about the weather

01:07:40.690 --> 01:07:42.460
but nobody ever does
anything about it.

01:07:42.460 --> 01:07:45.760
And John, you're a great
example of somebody

01:07:45.760 --> 01:07:49.140
who is both talking
about the environment

01:07:49.140 --> 01:07:51.900
that we're in, and not
just remarking upon it

01:07:51.900 --> 01:07:54.270
but building the
actual structures,

01:07:54.270 --> 01:07:57.740
the roles you've played in each
of these examples-- of course,

01:07:57.740 --> 01:07:59.950
something you wouldn't
naturally trumpet.

01:07:59.950 --> 01:08:02.590
But you have just been so
crucial to all of this.

01:08:02.590 --> 01:08:05.360
And for those reasons, it's not
just what you're writing about

01:08:05.360 --> 01:08:06.734
but what you're
doing that we are

01:08:06.734 --> 01:08:09.620
so lucky to have you in the
mix, and all of the things

01:08:09.620 --> 01:08:11.130
that you've done for us.

01:08:11.130 --> 01:08:13.390
So if you'll allow us
the uncomfortable moment

01:08:13.390 --> 01:08:15.320
of thanking you for
all your hard work.

01:08:15.320 --> 01:08:15.620
JOHN PALFREY: You're very kind.

01:08:15.620 --> 01:08:16.453
Thank you, everyone.

01:08:16.453 --> 01:08:19.220
[APPLAUSE]

01:08:21.962 --> 01:08:23.420
And thank you to
the Berkman Center

01:08:23.420 --> 01:08:26.720
and to the Harvard Law
School Library for hosting.

01:08:26.720 --> 01:08:29.120
I look forward to
seeing you next door.

01:08:29.120 --> 01:08:29.720
Thank you.

01:08:29.720 --> 01:08:31.570
JONATHAN ZITTRAIN: Thank you.

